<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estrada Seeks Elimination of Probation for Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
called on Congress Monday to enact measures designed to strengthen
and intensify the government's drive against illicit drugs and
other crimes.
</P>
<P>
In his first State of the Nation Address at the inaugural
session of the 11th Congress, Estrada said he wants, among other
things, the deletion of a provision in the Dangerous Drugs Act
that grants probation to offenders.
</P>
<P>
"I propose that Congress amend the Dangerous Drugs Act to
eliminate the possibility of probation for all offenders, even if
they say they are sorry. The only place for a drug dealer and the
addict is together in jail," he said.
</P>
<P>
To boost the government's battle against other lawless
elements, the chief executive also said Congress should amend the
Philippine National Police (PNP) Law so that police control will
devolve to the local government units.
</P>
<P>
Estrada expressed confidence that the devolved PNP will be more
effective in dealing with crimes within their areas of
jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive also took the opportunity to defend the
creation of the Presidential Task Force Against Organized Crime,
saying it is needed to "hit crime, and hit it hard, so as to put
it out decisively." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
