<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Ministry Says More Disaster Relief Work Is Needed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 27 (Xinhua) -- China's Civil Affairs Ministry
today asked local governments in flood-hit areas in southern China
to make better arrangements for their victims.
</P>
<P>
From mid-June to early July, Jiangxi, Hubei, Hunan, Guangdong,
Zhejiang, and Sichuan provinces and the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region and other areas south of the Yangtze River have been hit by
heavy rainfalls, causing floods and killing a number of people and
causing serious property losses.
</P>
<P>
More serious flooding has hit provinces on the middle and lower
reaches of the Yangtze and parts of northern China have entered
the flood season, while coastal areas in southeastern China are
being threatened by typhoons. The situation is very serious, the
Ministry says.
</P>
<P>
Governments in flood-hit areas need to try to provide
sufficient food, clothing, shelter, and medical supplies for
people in their areas, and should focus on moving people from
flood-stricken areas and providing shelter, the Ministry said. It
and the Ministry of Finance have already spent more than 300
million yuan (36 million U.S. dollars) on relief supplies.
</P>
<P>
It also said that civil affairs departments need to work on
preventing an outbreak of epidemic diseases. None has been
reported in disaster-stricken areas so far, but there is still a
great risk because of poor living conditions and the large number
of people in flooded areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
