<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chuan Pledges to Give Tourism All Possible Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
pledged Monday that his government will give the country's tourism
industry all possible assistance.
</P>
<P>
Chuan said that his government will do everything possible to
ensure that the industry receives all possible assistance in its
efforts to facilitate the national recovery and save Thai jobs.
</P>
<P>
Chuan made the remarks at a rewarding ceremony during which the
Thai tourism industry rewarded its best and brightest with a
series awards and commendations designed to encourage innovation
and sensitive development of the industry, the country's biggest
foreign currency earner.
</P>
<P>
The list of award-winners includes villages, national parks,
arts and culture centers, universities, museums and attractions
which have worked hard to improve their standards and product
quality to cater to both domestic and international tourists.
</P>
<P>
Awards were also given to tour operators, diplomats, university
professors, company chiefs and journalists who have played a major
role in promoting the Thai tourism industry over the years.
</P>
<P>
The awards reflect a desire of the Tourism Authority of
Thailand (TAT) to develop new products that can encourage visitors
to stay longer and spend more in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Thailand launched an "Amazing Thailand" campaign during 1998
and 1999, setting a target of 16 million foreign tourist arrivals
and 580 billion baht (14.5 billion U.S. dollars) income.
</P>
<P>
The government hoped that the boost of tourism will bring the
country its most-needed foreign currencies after the massive
foreign investment outflow following the outbreak of the financial
and economic crisis last July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
