<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alaska Military Commander Dies in Plane Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Air Force Lieutenant General
David J. McCloud, who commanded all military forces in Alaska,
died Sunday in a private plane crash.
</P>
<P>
McCloud was flying his YAK-54, a Russian-made, single-engine,
aerobatic plane, with a passenger on board, when it crashed in a
paratrooper drop zone at Fort Richardson east of Anchorage,
Alaska, on Sunday, the Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
The cause of the crash was not immediately available and the
National Transportation Safety Board is investigating.
</P>
<P>
As commander of the Alaskan Command, McCloud was responsible
for more than 21,000 active duty and reserve members of the
U.S. Army, Air Force, Navy and Alaska National Guard.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton, in a statement, called McCloud a
"superb airman and an exemplary leader."
</P>
<P>
Before coming to Alaska, McCloud worked at the Pentagon for the
Joint Chiefs of Staff as director for force structure, resources
and assessment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
