<HEADLINE> Greece: U.S. Officials' Statements Not in Harmony with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Greece said Monday that recent
statements made by U.S. officials were not in harmony with the
U.N. resolutions concerning the settlement of the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas said that relations between Greece and the United
States were "at a good level," but there was room for further
improvement.
</P>
<P>
Good relations between countries must be based on mutual
respect, plain speech and a common understanding of issues of
mutual interest, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. initiative on the Cyprus issue had begun with a high
tone and the cultivation of expectations, he said, adding that
Washington would now decide at what pace the initiative develops.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that Greece would always express
objections when it perceived that there was a lack of sincerity
and the initiative did not reflect overall U.N. stances.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Reppas complained that the international community
had been lacking in not responding to Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides' proposal for the demilitarization of Cyprus while
pressures had not been brought to bear on neighboring Turkey to
make it comply with the demands of the international community.
</P>
<P>
He said that anyone who approaches the Cyprus problem solely
from the viewpoint of Nicosia's plans to deploy the Russian-made
S-300 anti-aircraft missile was either totally ignorant of history
or had other designs in mind. 
</P>
</TEXT>
