<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Talks on Southern African Customs Union Going </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Negotiations to resolve
issues relating to the Southern African Customs Union (SACU) were
proceeding in good faith despite their complexity, South African
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki has said.
</P>
<P>
He was addressing leaders from the 14 Southern African
Development Community (SADC) countries at an international dialog
forum in Swakopmund, a coastal city of Namibia, South African
Press Association (SAPA) reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We are, all of us as members of the customs union, very keen
to move forward with that process," Mbeki said Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
"It is complicated because it also relates to the future of
the SADC, which also has to relate to the negotiations with the
European Union (EU). It is wrong to pretend that it is possible
to answer any of those questions easily."
</P>
<P>
He said discussions on the customs issue had proceeded slowly,
but everyone involved had acted in good faith in dealing with
complex questions.
</P>
<P>
SAPA quoted insiders in the SACU negotiations as saying that
South Africa controlled almost everything and secretly decided
how much each member country should receive. This, they said,
was unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
SACU members draw a large portion of their total revenue from
the customs union pool. All SACU members -- Namibia, Botswana,
Lesotho, Swaziland and South Africa -- belong to SADC.
</P>
<P>
SADC countries are negotiating the establishment of a free
trade area, which would threaten the existence of the SACU. Other
SADC member countries desire a relaxation of laws and regulations
governing the customs union to allow them a reasonable share of
profits.
</P>
<P>
The customs union's existence has also been threatened by free
trade negotiations between South Africa and the EU as massive
inflow of cheap EU exports would hurt economies of other SACU
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
