<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estrada Calls for Unity in Overcoming Economic Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
Monday appealed to all sectors to help his administration in
crafting quick and effective solutions to the country's nagging
problems.
</P>
<P>
In his first state of the nation address, Estrada plumbed the
depth of the nation's woes and offered reforms to slam the brakes
on the economic downturn and handcuff criminals and corrupt
government officials who helped push the country to the edge.
</P>
<P>
Speaking mostly in Filipino, he begged for time and
understanding, and offered a covenant of unity with the people so
that together they can tackle the problems that threaten to
undermine his campaign pledge help the poor.
</P>
<P>
Estrada also stressed that contrary to earlier statistics, the
country's poor has become poorer, and the rich has become richer
while the economy is drowning in red ink, with a 2.3-trillion-peso
(about 54.76 billion U.S. dollars) public sector tab, 70-billion
peso (about 1.67 billion dollars) budget deficit, double digit
inflation, and swelling unemployment rate.
</P>
<P>
But the immensity of the problems neither means that the
government is helpless against them nor that the people are
powerless to help tackle them, he said.
</P>
<P>
He credited his predecessor, former president Ramos, for the
economic reforms that enabled the country to continue posting
positive growth while neighbors in the region registered negative
gross national product (GNP).
</P>
<P>
Despite the "formidable odds" arrayed by the regionwide
economic turmoil, he said he expected economic growth, as the GNP
is targeted to expand by 2 to 3 percent this year and inflation is
kept in the single digit, at around 9.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Faced with mounting woes, Estrada underscored the need to
undertake measures to cut spending, raise revenues and stamp out
graft and corruption.
</P>
<P>
He also asked the congress to give him the authority to
reorganize the government to make it truly effective, efficient,
responsive and accountable.
</P>
<P>
As to the peace and order problem, he said it is time to mount
an all-out war against criminals whose nefarious activities have
scared away investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
