<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Won Gains Strength Against Greenback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean won strengthened to
1,211 against the U.S. dollar since last December when the country
was gripped by a financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Opening at 1,245 against the dollar Monday, the won appreciated
to 1,208 in the morning and closed the day at 1,211.
</P>
<P>
The won, which closed at 1,695 at the end of last year and
traded at around 1,400 won for months, lost more than 40 percent
of its value in the wake the financial crisis caused by corporate
bankruptcies and bad loans of financial institutions last year.
</P>
<P>
After reaching 1,695 won against the dollar, the won gradually
found strength at 1,525 at the end of January this year, 1,383 at
the end of March, 1,373 at the end of June, and to 1,245 over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
Observers attribute the won's appreciation to an abundance of
dollars on the market stemming from current account surpluses and
the introduction of foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
If this trend continues, it will be easy to break the 1,200 won
level against the greenback in the immediate future, they said.
</P>
<P>
South Korean exporters have expressed worries that the won's
renewed strength might damage the country's exports, prompting
speculation on possible government intervention.
</P>
<P>
However, the Ministry of Finance and Economy recently denied
the rumors saying the government would leave the fate of the won
to market forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Pledges to Help End Angolan War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 27 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will do its
best to help both parties in the Angolan conflict find a peaceful
solution, South African Defense Minister Joe Modise said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"South Africa will redouble its efforts to bring both parties
to a peaceful settlement," South African Press Association (SAPA)
quoted Modise as saying.
</P>
<P>
Modise said a renewed civil war in Angola would affect the
entire southern African region and that South Africa was
extremely concerned about the worsening situation in that
country.
</P>
<P>
The defense minister added that another war in Angola would
also exacerbate the refugee problem in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"There are already two million refugees, some from as far as
Somalia, in South Africa," he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to repeated reports of the illegal trafficking of
weapons and supplies to Angola's warring parties, Modise said
that his government would do its utmost to thwart gun-running
from South Africa to Angola.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that none of our people are involved in this kind of
thing and if any are, they face very heavy sentences," he warned.
</P>
<P>
The latest setback to the Angolan peace process came with the
recent massacre of about 200 villagers in Angola's Lunda Norte
province.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government blamed the National Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) for the attack, but UNITA denied
it, saying that the massacre was the result of the tension
between the Angolans and the foreign diamond traffickers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
