<HEADLINE> Sino-Japanese Summer Camp In Northwestern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Tenth Sino-Japanese Youth
Friendly Exchange Summer Camp started today in Urumqi, capital of
northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Some 19 Japanese middle and primary school students and three
Chinese middle school students from Xinjiang will visit Uygur
ethnic group families, the Mogao Grotto in the city of Dunhuang,
Gansu Province, and Jiayu Pass on the western end of the Great
Wall in Gansu, and go camping on a grassland there.
</P>
<P>
In the past, more than 300 Japanese and 100 Chinese youths from
Xinjiang have participated in the summer camps, and about 30
Chinese from Xinjiang have visited Japan.
</P>
<P>
The program was started in 1989 by a regional sports commission
official and a Japanese professor from Japan's Fukuoka Education
University. 
