<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Observers Happy With Election Proceeding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 27 (Xinhua) -- International observers,
monitoring the Cambodian election, said Monday that the voting was
basically free and fair, fueling hopes that the election could be
a success.
</P>
<P>
Cambodians went to polls en masse on Sunday to vote in historic
elections that are expected to give the country a second chance
for peace, stability and a legitimate government.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodian National Election Committee (NEC) reported a
massive voter turnout of more than 90 percent, a much higher
figure than expected.
</P>
<P>
Glenys Kinnock, the European Union's chief observer, said she
was pleasantly surprised at the turnout, given reports of voter
intimidation.
</P>
<P>
"There was an enormous enthusiasm by the voters ... The crush
was fantastic," said Kinnock, who visited polling stations in
Kandal, Kompong Speu and Takeo provinces. "As always, the people
surprise you."
</P>
<P>
International monitors reported few cases of violence, ballot
stuffing or serious intimidation, she said, adding that reports
"generally have been favorable."
</P>
<P>
But she warned that "it's not time for euphoria either." She
said the counting process and acceptance of the results are still
to come. "Now we go on to the next hurdle, the next series of
hurdles."
</P>
<P>
Partial results are expected as early as late Monday, with the
ruling Cambodian People's Party, the ousted Funcinpec, and the
upstart Sam Rainsy Party all hoping to lead what most expect will
be another coalition government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
