<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prolonged Slump Expected for South Korea's Export Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 27 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's export industries,
except auto and semiconductor exporters, will see a protracted
slump by the end of this year, the Korea Chamber of Commerce and
Industry (KCCI) said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Exports by the steel industry are expected to fall 5.8 percent
in the second half of this year due to a series of bankruptcies by
local steel makers.
</P>
<P>
On a yearly basis, the nation's steel production will likely
mark its first negative growth by falling 12.7 percent, said the
KCCI.
</P>
<P>
Production of general machinery and construction sector orders
in the second half will also decline by 24.5 percent and 59.6
percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, eight out of the nation's 10 major private think
tanks, which serve as research institutes for conglomerates, said
in a poll that it would be impossible for the nation to attain a
trade surplus of 50 billion U.S. dollars in 1998, as targeted by
the Federation of Korean Industries, a club of family-run chaebols.
</P>
<P>
The think tanks attribute the prolonged economic slump to a
credit crunch stemming from financial restructuring, which they
say will worsen the business climate.
</P>
<P>
The Hyundai Research Institute said that up to one million more
workers will lose jobs this year and South Korea would not be able
to return to a per-capita gross domestic product (GDP) of 10,000
U.S. dollars and an annual GDP growth of 5 percent even by 2002 if
no measures were taken.
</P>
<P>
However, the KCCI, in its business forecast for the second half
of 1998, said the nation's semiconductor exports in the second
half of this year will soar 41.2 percent, based on stable
international prices of 16- and 64-mega DRAMs and brisk Christmas
sales.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, South Korean auto manufacturers are expected
to increase exports 31.1 percent from the first half of this year
and 19.6 percent from a year earlier because of rising exports of
new models. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
