<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Holds Talks With Eritrean President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Eritrean President Isaias Afworki
arrived in the Mediterranean port city of Alexandria Monday for
talks with President Hosni Mubarak on the worsening border row in
the Horn of Africa.
</P>
<P>
According to the Middle East News Agency, the talks of the two
president in the Ras el-Teen Palace will focus on ways to resolve
the border dispute between Eritrea and Ethiopia, and on the Middle
East peace process stalemate as well.
</P>
<P>
Afworki had exchanged views with Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi
in Tripoli before coming to Cairo to continue his multi-leg
African tour.
</P>
<P>
The Eritrean president, who had sent two messages to Mubarak in
June, is expected to seek an active role from the Egyptian leader
in halting the developing Ethiopia-Eritrea border conflict.
</P>
<P>
Eritrean Foreign Minister Haile Weldensae, after meeting with
Mubarak on June 14, told reporters that Mubarak "promised to do
his best and contact the Ethiopian side in order to reach a
ceasefire between the two parties and to bring about a peaceful
solution."
</P>
<P>
But recent remarks by Egyptian officials suggested that Cairo
is not going to spearhead the mediation effort despite repeated
appeals from both sides.
</P>
<P>
Marawan Badr, the Egyptian ambassador to Ethiopia, last week
said Cairo supported and participated in an Organization of
African Unity (OAU) resolution on the conflict during its recent
summit in Burkina Faso, and denied the Cairo has launched a new
initiative.
</P>
<P>
The OAU has sent four African presidents, of Burkina Faso,
Djibouti, Zimbabwe and Rwanda, to Ethiopia and Eritrea in a
renewed effort to end the hostilities.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt is adopting a neutral stand vis-a-vis the dispute due to
the importance of its ties with both countries," Badr said in an
interview with "Ethiopian Herald" last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea have accused each other of incursions
since bloody clashes broke out over a 400 square kilometer rocky
triangle of land along their western border.
</P>
<P>
The conflict deteriorated recently, dashing the hope that
U.S.-led mediation would bring about a ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak had sent messages to the two countries' leaders,
calling for an immediate end to fighting, and negotiations to
resolve the border row.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea and Ethiopia, among the world's poorest, are at odds
over at least six areas along their common border. Eritrea gained
independence from Ethiopia in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
