<HEADLINE> Banned Dufaux Confesses Taking Doping For Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Swiss rider Laurent Dufaux, who was
banned from the Tour de France for doping, confessed on Monday
that he took performance-enhancing hormone EPO for three years.
</P>
<P>
"I took it for three years under strict medical supervision.
But I never abused it," Dufaux said in an interview with Swiss
daily Le Matin.
</P>
<P>
Dufaux, who was fourth in the 1996 Tour de France, and four of
his Festina teammates have admitted taking banned substances to
improve their performance, and the team director Bruno Roussel
confirmed they took part in an systematic doping.
</P>
<P>
The Tour de France then banned Festina riders to compete in
the race, including Alex Zulle, Armin Meier, Richard Virenque,
etc., though some of them denied taking dopes.
</P>
<P>
Dufaux said doping problem is much beyond people's thinkings,
but the cycling authority would make the confessed five scapegoats
rather than take more fierce measure to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
"I am afraid people will put a lid over the five who have
confessed, that they will be sanctioned and that nothing will
change," Dufaux said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
