<HEADLINE> PNA Welcomes Egyptian-Syrian Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) Monday expressed welcome to Sunday's summit between Egypt
and Syria, the Egyptian Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Nabil Abu Redina, spokesman for PNA President Yasser Arafat,
told the news agency in a telephone interview that Palestinians
welcome the coordination between Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
and his Syrian counterpart Hafez al-Assad.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Assad held a meeting on Sunday in Egypt's
Mediterranean port city of Alexandria on the latest developments
of the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Redina said the Palestinians desire to maintain a unified
Palestinian-Syrian stance on the Arab-Israeli peace talks, and the
PNA is in constant contact with Arab leaders in a bid to adopt a
unified Arab stand to confront Israeli intransigence.
</P>
<P>
He said Arafat will address the upcoming ministerial meetings
of the Jerusalem Committee of the Organization of the Islamic
Conference, to be held in Morocco on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have called on the committee to help maintain
the status of the holy city against Israel's judaization schemes.
</P>
<P>
On the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks, Redina said the
negotiations between the two sides last week yielded "nothing new"
regarding Israel's attitude towards a United States proposal on
its troop withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has reportedly called on Israel to withdraw from 13.1
percent more of the West Bank. The PNA has accepted the proposal,
but the Jewish state resisted it.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman denied there is any arrangement for a meeting
between Arafat and Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai or
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Arafat insists such a meeting depends on Israel's acceptance of
the U.S. proposal, he said. 
</P>
