<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Suspense Arises Over Election Outcome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 27 (Xinhua) -- As ballot counting began amid
reports of unexpectedly high voter turnout in Sunday's election,
suspense arose over whether the vote would lead to another
coalition or political deadlock in strife-stricken Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Three main parties vying to control the new National Assembly
were set to split the vote and no single party would be likely to
obtain an outright majority to form a government, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Incumbent Co-Premier Hun Sen's Cambodian People's Party (CPP),
the Funcinpec party of the rival first-premier he ousted last
year, Prince Norodom Ranariddh, and the party of former finance
minister Sam Rainsy, which bears his name, were expected to become
the backbone of Cambodia's politics after the election.
</P>
<P>
But for a party to form a government, it needs a two-thirds
majority in the 122-member National Assembly, or 82 seats, which
is an unrealistically high figure in the eyes of many observers.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the election appears certain to result in a
coalition government, which is only a year after the last one
collapsed in violence.
</P>
<P>
The CPP was expected to become the largest party in the
assembly and would have to form a coalition with either Funcinpec
or the Sam Rainsy Party, or possibly even both, with the CPP
naming the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The CPP has ruled Cambodia since the early 1980s and is
believed to enjoy strong support in the countryside. With control
over the armed forces, police, judiciary and media, the party
apparently maintains an upper hand in the political field in a
country where democracy is having a hard time taking root.
</P>
<P>
But Funcinpec and the Sam Rainsy Party are also forces to be
reckoned with. The factors that led to Funcinpec winning most
seats in Cambodia's last election in 1993 are still at work,
analysts said. Funcinpec can also count on a solid base of royal
sentiment among the masses.
</P>
<P>
The Sam Rainsy Party, a strong opponent of corruption and an
advocate for human rights, also enjoys much support, particularly
among the youth.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts are betting on a coalition between Funcinpec and
the CPP as the most likely possibility. But Prince Ranariddh told
Xinhua that he would never work again in a government led by the
CPP, making the viability of such an alliance doubtful.
</P>
<P>
A more pessimistic scenario foresees a breakdown in coalition
talks and an ensuing political deadlock. A Western diplomat
pointed to the possibility of a constitutional crisis if a major
party obstructs the 70 percent quorum required to convene the
National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The chance of a constitutional crisis does exist because of
this absurd situation of a two-thirds quorum, said the diplomat.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to dismiss fears over post-election violence by the
CPP if it failed to secure political power in the election, Hun
Sen told reporters he would quit politics if the CPP did not win.
</P>
<P>
Whatever the outcome, international observers monitoring the
voting have expressed satisfaction over the election which has
been peaceful, contrary to previous predictions about its
disruption and reports of voter intimidation.
</P>
<P>
"Cambodia has undergone great changes as the political struggle
has tilted towards elections instead of the force of arms," said
Karen Hill, a member of the Joint International Observers
Group. "There is reason to be optimistic about Cambodia's future."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
