<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Hit Wuyuan, Leping in Jiangxi Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Floods from torrential rains that
lasted for one week have severely stricken the Wuyuan County and
Leping city along the Le'an River in east China's Jiangxi Province.
</P>
<P>
About 28 townships and 60 percent of the residents in Wuyuan
County were affected by the floods, which have destroyed more than
12,000 houses and reduced the local early-rice output by half.
</P>
<P>
The area reported record-high rainfalls, and lasting heavy
rains triggered mud flow and pushed the water level in the Le'an
River to 2.65 meters above the warning level, according to local
governments.
</P>
<P>
Water-swollen Le'an River also posed severe damage to the
Leping City on the lower reaches of the river. Floods have
inundated eight townships in the area and put 180,000 people in
danger.
</P>
<P>
The rising floods have damaged about 129.6 kilometers of flood
barriers around the Leping City, and breached some of the dikes.
</P>
<P>
So far, about 1,116 industrial enterprises in Leping have
broken down due to the suspension of transportation and power
supply. 
</P>
</TEXT>
