<HEADLINE> Italy Extends Medium-Term Credit to Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Italy has agreed on Monday to
extend a medium-term credit of 1.2 billion U.S. dollars to Iran,
to help promote their trade and industrial cooperation.
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency IRNA, an agreement on the
loan was signed by Italian Bank Mediobanca and six Iranian banks.
</P>
<P>
The credit will facilitate small and medium-sized industries
of the two countries to launch cooperation programs and set up
joint ventures, the report said, giving no more details.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iran's Minister of Mines and Metals Ishaq Jahangiri
and visiting Italian Minister of Foreign Trade Augusto Fantozzi
signed a letter of understanding on economic and trade cooperation
at the end of the third session of joint Iran-Italy economic
commission.
</P>
<P>
In the document, Iran and Italy agree to diversify Tehran's
non-oil exports to Rome in order to expand bilateral exchange and
to create balance in Tehran-Rome trade.
</P>
<P>
Italy would export industries to help Iran's industrial
development, the document said, and the two countries agree on
promoting cooperation between small and medium-sized industries
through providing credit facilities.
</P>
<P>
The Italian side said its insurance companies are to provide
services to small and medium-sized industries in Iran as of July
28.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also underlined the need for expanding air
and land transportation between the two sides to address the
growing trade relations. 
</P>
