<HEADLINE> India Develops 15-Year Renewable Energy Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- India's Ministry of
Non-Conventional Energy would soon implement a 15-year renewable
energy program to augment grid electricity supply and substitute
fossil fuels in decentralized applications, said a report issued
by the ministry here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The country-wide program aims at achieving a 10 percent share
of renewable energy in the total installed capacity for grid
electricity by the year 2012. It is proposed to provide
electricity by means of solar, biomass, small hydro and wind
energy to all 80,000 non-electrified villages and households in a
phased manner by 2012, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It also aims at improving the quality of energy supply to rural
areas for bringing about an all round development through the
integrated rural energy program which would be expanded to cover
all blocks of the country by 2012.
</P>
<P>
The renewable program would address issues relating to
institutional arrangements, financial resource mobilization,
promotion of industry and human resource development necessary for
large scale utilization of renewable energy, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
