<HEADLINE> Russia Urges South Korea to Allow Ousted Diplomat Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 27 (Xinhua) -- South Korea will be able to settle
its diplomatic dispute with Russia if it allows Oleg Abramkin, an
ousted Russian counselor, to return to the Russian Embassy in
Seoul, a Russian diplomat said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"To put an end to the diplomatic conflict, Seoul should make
this kind of symbolic gesture of reconciliation," Valery Suhinin,
minister-counselor of the Russian Embassy in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
Suhinin said that Abramkin was a victim of a diplomatic
dispute, insisting that the expelled Russian did nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
South Korean intelligence officers claimed they have evidence
Abramkin went beyond his diplomatic status in collecting sensitive
intelligence in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The Russian diplomat's ouster came three days after Moscow's
expulsion of Cho Sung-woo, a counselor of the South Korean Embassy
in Moscow, on spy charges on July 4 this year.
</P>
<P>
If Abramkin, who had been scheduled to return to Russia in
September this year, is allowed to stay until then, Suhinin said,
the diplomatic conflict will be settled.
</P>
<P>
"Without Abramkin's reinstatement, the case will remain a
thorny issue blocking the improvement of relations between the two
countries,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Suhinin said that Russia does not intend to take advantage of
the diplomatic row, or to put pressure on South Korea to make some
concessions on pending issues.
</P>
<P>
During the ASEAN Regional Forum, South Korean Foreign Minister
Park Chung-soo and his Russian counterpart Yevgeni Primakov met in
Manila, the Philippines, on Sunday to discuss the diplomatic
row. They failed to narrow their differences. Primakov reportedly
insisted that South Korea allow Abramkin to return to Seoul, but
Park refused.
</P>
<P>
Before the diplomatic conflict, the two countries enjoyed good
relations since the establishment of full diplomatic ties in
1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
