<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ARF Ends Meeting After Discussions on Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF)
ended its annual meeting here Monday afternoon after discussions
on security issues of the Asia-Pacific region cooperation between
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and its
dialogue partners.
</P>
<P>
In a closing statement issued at the end of the meeting, this
year's ARF chairman and Philippine Secretary of Foreign Affairs
Domingo Siazon said the participating ministers "exchanged views
on issues which have great bearing on the security environment of
the Asia-Pacific."
</P>
<P>
"We held productive dialogue on the various issues confronting
our region today and had a deeper and more intensive appreciation
of these issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ministers discussed "extensively" the prevailing financial
situation in the region and exchanged views on the factors that
caused the crisis and on how they should cooperate more closely in
meeting the challenges posed by it, according to Siazon.
</P>
<P>
Calling the one-day meeting "very productive," the statement
said, "once again we have proven that peace and security in our
region is indivisible and can be advanced through active dialogue
and coordination."
</P>
<P>
"As we conclude the Fifth ASEAN Regional Forum," Siazon said in
the statement, "I can say that all of us have contributed to the
evolution of the ARF as a process for building trust and
confidence, for creating a favorable climate for peace and
understanding and for fostering the habit of consultation."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that it has been proven since the first meeting
in Bangkok in 1994 that "the ARF works and it has evolved as a
mechanism for addressing regional peace and security issues while
at the same time bridging gaps in the diverse interests of its
participants."
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting were foreign ministers or representatives
from the nine ASEAN member countries, the two observer nations and
the 10 dialogue partners.
</P>
<P>
Siazon noted that "exuding a spirit of commitment to see the
entire Asia-Pacific region working toward peace and security, we
welcomed the participation of Mongolia in the ARF."
</P>
<P>
"With the entry of Mongolia into the forum, we take another
step toward completing the geographical footprint of the ARF," he
added.
</P>
<P>
He expressed welcome to Japan's assurances that Japan will
revitalize its economy and those of Chinese Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan that the value of the Chinese currency will be maintained.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the ARF's future direction, Siazon said, "We
acknowledged that decision-making by consensus is as valid then as
it is today."
</P>
<P>
A chairman statement was also issued at the end of the meeting,
spelling out the ARF's positions on issues ranging from Cambodian
elections to nuclear tests in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
The ARF, which held its first meeting in Bangkok four years
ago, is now attended by the ASEAN's members including Brunei,
Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore,
Thailand and Vietnam; its 10 dialogue partners -- Australia,
Canada, China, the European Union, India, Japan, New Zealand,
Russia, South Korea and the United States -- and its two observers
Cambodia and Papua New Guinea.
</P>
<P>
China obtained its full dialogue partner status in 1996
although it had joined ASEAN member countries as guest during
ASEAN Ministerial Meetings from 1991. Tang Jiaxuan, the Chinese
foreign minister, addressed the meeting and expounded China's
positions on regional security issues.
</P>
<P>
Initiated by the ASEAN in 1993, the ARF is a consultative forum
aimed at promoting confidence building, developing preventive
diplomacy and working out approaches to conflicts among states in
the Asia-Pacific region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
