<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Shares Tumble as Tokyo's Nikkei Slides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- A slide on the Tokyo stock market
Monday pulled the Australian bourse one percent lower, with major
companies News Corp, National Australia Bank and BHP losing
ground.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index ended 30.2 points softer at
2715.3 while the Tokyo's Nikkei index tumbled 417.53 points as
investors remained nervous.
</P>
<P>
"We were watching Tokyo and the yen today and that led us
lower. News out of Japan seems to be that the new Prime Minister
is just more of the same," Reynolds &AMP; Co's Grant Williams said.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials shed 51.8 points to 4774.8 and the all
resources index lost 12.9 to 1052.2.
</P>
<P>
Media stocks were particularly hard hit.
</P>
<P>
Telstra, which topped the turnover table with 8.29 million
shares traded, ended steady at 4.59 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Financial services giant AMP rallied 17 cents to 19.92
Australian dollars. Colonial shares rose four cents.
</P>
<P>
Among resource stocks, BHP shed 12 cents to close, and Rio
Tinto slipped eight after reporting that production of most
commodities increased over its second quarter. Woodside lost 12
cents, and Caltex tumbled 20 cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold index gave up 19.9 points or 1.8 percent to finish at
1080.6 as the spot price for the precious metal was selling 290.60
U.S. dollars an ounce.
</P>
<P>
The banking index held up a little better, shedding 57.5
percent or 0.95 percent to 6010.6. ANZ ended 21 cents softer, CBA
closed 23 lower, NAB decreased 16 and Westpac came back 7.1 to
10.45 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was a modest 233.10 million valued at 790.75
million Australian dollars (490.4 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
