<HEADLINE> ARF Optimistic Over Asia's Economic Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The foreign ministers participating
in the 5th ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF) Monday expressed optimism
that confidence in Asia would quickly return as the financial
crisis-hit economies carry out the necessary structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
"They (the ministers) expressed optimism that, as the affected
economies implement the necessary structural reforms, confidence
would increasingly return," Philippine Foreign Secretary Domingo
Siazon said in the ARF chairman statement issued after the forum.
</P>
<P>
Siazon, who is currently the rotating chairman of the ARF, said
that the ministers discussed extensively the region's prevailing
financial situation and they were encouraged by initial signs of
progress toward financial stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also expressed full confidence that the economies
of East Asia would eventually regain their position as among the
fastest-growing economies in the world, he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting the interdependence among Asian economies, the ministers
welcomed the assurances of Japan that it will revitalize its
economy as well as the assurances of China that the value of the
yuan will be maintained.
</P>
<P>
While recognizing the need for structural reforms in restoring
confidence, Siazon said, the ministers called for a balanced
approach in addressing the socio-economic impact of such reforms,
particularly its impact on the less privileged sectors of society.
</P>
<P>
The ministers noted that certain aspects of the regional
financial crisis could have impact on the peace and security of
the region and agreed that the ARF would have an important role to
play in addressing these effects.
</P>
<P>
The ARF participants also agreed that the current Asian
economic difficulties should not undermine the process of the ARF
and other regional security dialogues and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The ARF was attended by the foreign ministers from the nine
ASEAN member countries and the 10 ASEAN dialogue partners, and
representatives from the two ASEAN observer nations of Cambodia
and Papua New Guinea.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups the Philippines, Thailand, Singapore, Malaysia,
Vietnam, Indonesia, Brunei, Laos and Myanmar. The 10 ASEAN
dialogue partners are the United States, Japan, China, the
European Union, Australia, Canada, New Zealand, India, South Korea
and Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
