<HEADLINE> ARF Supports Peace Process on Korean Peninsula </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The 5th ASEAN (Association of
Southeast Asian Nations) Regional Forum (ARF) Monday expressed its
"full and continued" support for the peace talks between the
Republic of Korea (ROK) and the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
"The ministers (participating in the forum) reiterated their
full and continued support for the talks and the KEDO (Korean
Energy Development Organization) project to help establish a
durable peace and stability on the Korean Peninsula and promote
global nuclear non-proliferation," said Philippine Foreign
Secretary Domingo Siazon in the ARF chairman statement.
</P>
<P>
In the statement issued at the end of the one-day forum,
Siazon, currently holding the rotating ARF's chairmanship, said
that in view of the current financial difficulties that the KEDO
is facing, the forum called for more international contribution to
this organization.
</P>
<P>
During the annual ministerial forum, Siazon said, the ministers
welcomed the resumption of official dialogue between the ROK and
the DPRK in Beijing and the launching of the Four-Party Talks
Peace Process on the Korean Peninsula in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
The forum also emphasized the vital importance of the
inter-Korean dialogue in promoting reconciliation and cooperation
between the ROK and the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
The peace process on the Korean Peninsula was one of the topics
tackled by the ARF which also included the nuclear arms race in
South Asia, the prolonged Asian financial crisis, and regional
security environment.
</P>
<P>
The ARF was attended by the foreign ministers from the nine
ASEAN member countries and the 10 ASEAN dialogue partners, as well
as representatives from the two ASEAN observer nations Cambodia
and Papua New Guinea.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups the Philippines, Malaysia, Brunei, Vietnam, Laos,
Myanmar, Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore. The regional grouping
will hold a series of post ministerial conferences Tuesday with
its 10 ASEAN dialogue partners -- the United States, China, Japan,
Canada, New Zealand, the European Union, Australia, the Republic
of Korea, India and Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
