<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ARF Praised for Contribution to Regional Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Ministers attending the ASEAN
Regional Forum (ARF), which ended its annual meeting here Monday
afternoon, praised the ARF as "an important forum for dialogue on
political and security concerns in the region."
</P>
<P>
In a chairman's statement issued at the end of the meeting,
Philippine Secretary of Foreign Affairs Domingo Siazon said the
ministers "recognized the significant contribution of the ARF to
the establishment of a strong foundation of trust and confidence
among its participants, which would be essential in confronting
the existing uncertainties in the Asia-Pacific region."
</P>
<P>
The statement noted that the ARF process has contributed to the
achievement of greater transparency and mutual understanding in
the region, which had instilled among its participants "a high
sense of collective commitment to regional peace and stability."
</P>
<P>
The ARF, which held its first meeting in Bangkok four years
ago, is now attended by the ASEAN's nine members including Brunei,
Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore,
Thailand and Vietnam; its 10 dialogue partners -- Australia,
Canada, China, the European Union, India, Japan, New Zealand,
Russia, South Korea and the United States -- and its two observers
Cambodia and Papua New Guinea.
</P>
<P>
At this year's ASEAN meetings, Mongolia was endorsed as a new
participant in the ARF, which, initiated by the ASEAN in 1993, is
a consultative forum aimed at promoting confidence building,
developing preventive diplomacy and working out approaches to
conflicts among states in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
The ministers at their meeting agreed that the ARF "should
continue its steady progress to successfully carry through its
goals in face of even greater challenges in the future," according
to the statement.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed that "the full support of all ARF participants
to the ARF's evolutionary, step-by-step development and its
approach to decision-making by consensus had contributed to the
ARF's resiliency as a viable regional forum for political and
security dialogue, encouraged open and frank discussions among ARF
participants and fostered the habit of cooperation and of
resolutely working together to address common concerns."
</P>
<P>
"The ARF had been living up to its potential and to the
important role it had been envisioned to play in further
strengthening the foundations for regional peace and stability,"
the statement declared.
</P>
<P>
The ministers commended ASEAN for its important contribution to
the ARF process and expressed their support to ASEAN's continuing
role as the primary driving force of the ARF, it noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
