<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ARF Meeting Deplores Nuke Tests in South Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF),
which ended its annual meeting here Monday afternoon, "expressed
grave concern over and strongly deplored" the nuclear tests
conducted by India and Pakistan in May.
</P>
<P>
A chairman's statement issued at the end of the meeting said
the participating ministers "called for the total cessation of
such testing and urged them to sign the Treaty on the
Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons and the Comprehensive Nuclear
Test Ban Treaty without delay, conditions or reservations."
</P>
<P>
Saying the tests "exacerbated tension in the region and raised
the specter of a nuclear arms race," they also asked the two
countries "to refrain from undertaking weaponization or deploying
missiles to deliver nuclear weapons and to prevent any transfer of
nuclear weapon-related materials, technology and equipment to
third countries."
</P>
<P>
"In the interest of peace and security in the region, the
ministers called on India and Pakistan to resolve their dispute
and security concerns through peaceful dialogue," according to the
statement.
</P>
<P>
The ministers recalled that as early as 1995 the ARF put
emphasis on the importance of non-proliferation of nuclear weapons
in promoting regional peace and security.
</P>
<P>
They also expressed support for efforts to establish nuclear
weapons-free zones and noted the importance of the Treaty on
Southeast Asia Nuclear Weapons Free Zone in enhancing peace and
security in the region.
</P>
<P>
In addition, they called for the immediate beginning of
negotiations in the Conference on Disarmament on a treaty banning
the production of fissile material for nuclear weapons purposes,
according to the statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
