<HEADLINE> ARF Welcomes "Generally Peaceful" Elections in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-one foreign ministers
attending the ASEAN annual meetings here Monday expressed their
support for the "generally peaceful" elections in Cambodia Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"The ministers welcomed the huge voter turnout in the July 26,
1998, elections and the initial reports that the voting process
was generally peaceful," Philippine Foreign Secretary Domingo
Siazon said in his chairman statement of the one-day Fifth ASEAN
Regional Forum (ARF).
</P>
<P>
They expressed the hope that the next stages of counting
ballots and the proclamation of the winners will also be peaceful
and orderly, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The ministers agreed that the holding of free, fair and
credible elections in Cambodia is an important step towards
enhancing peace and stability in Cambodia," Siazon added.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, he said, the ministers acknowledged the work of
international observers who monitored the electoral process under
the United Nations' coordination.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also declared AFR's "strong support" for the
efforts of the ASEAN and the "Friends of Cambodia" in helping
restore political stability and the climate of peace in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN includes Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. ASEAN decided to
delay the admission of Cambodia into ASEAN last year due to newly
emerged political unrest in the country.
</P>
<P>
The "Friends of Cambodia", a private group including Japan, the
United States, Russia, the European Union and some other donors,
has been working for the restoration of peace and stability in
Cambodia since last year.
</P>
<P>
In a joint communique issued here earlier, ASEAN foreign
ministers expressed their wish for "free, fair, credible and
successful" polls in Cambodia and reiterated their support to have
Cambodia as a new ASEAN member.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Foreign Undersecretary Lauro Baja said Cambodia's
admission to the ASEAN will depend on the outcome of the general
elections.
</P>
<P>
ARF presently consists of the nine ASEAN member countries, the
10 ASEAN dialogue partners (Australia, Canada, China, the European
Union, India, Japan, New Zealand, South Korea, Russia and the
U.S.) and the two observers Cambodia and Papua New Guinea.
</P>
</TEXT>
