<HEADLINE> More People Killed in Flood in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from flood has risen
to 110 in Bangladesh as of Monday with the number of
flood-affected people going up to 11 million, Jawadul Karim, press
secretary to Prime Minister Sheik Hasina, said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Of the 36 flood-hit districts, the situation has deteriorated
in 18 districts, improved in 12 districts, and remained unchanged
in six districts, Karim told a press briefing at the prime
minister's office.
</P>
<P>
The situation is expected to improve in the extreme northern
districts along the Brahmaputra-Jamuna river and in the
southeastern hill basin, but will aggravate in the northwestern
districts along the Ganges river and in the central part of
country in the next 24 hours, according to a bulletin available at
the briefing.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen deaths were reported during the past 24 hours, but
press reports here put the number at 165, with 115,934 acres of
crops washed away or submerged, 2,935 kilometers of road damaged
and 2,500 kilometers of embankments ravaged.
</P>
<P>
Many of the flood victims have been made homeless, with more
than 56,000 evacuated to 133 shelters, the press secretary said.
</P>
<P>
Some 3,313 medical teams have been sent to the flood-stricken
areas, where over 7,560 people have caught water-borne diseases
with 7 of them died.
</P>
<P>
The Disaster Management and Relief Ministry on Monday allocated
300 tons of foodgrains and 500,000 taka (about 10,600 U.S.
dollars) in cash for the flood victims, a ministry official said
at the briefing.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has so far granted more than 6.9 million taka
(about 146,700 dollars) in cash and 4,400 tons of foodgrains for
the flood-hit people.
</P>
<P>
Flood is very common in Bangladesh, as 70-80 percent of the
country's annual rainfall concentrates in the July-October monsoon
season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
