<HEADLINE> Daimler, Nissan to Jointly Develop Light Trucks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 27 (Xinhua) -- German automaker Daimler-Benz signed
an agreement on Monday with Japanese truck maker Nissan Diesel to
jointly develop a light commercial vehicle.
</P>
<P>
Daimler said the new model is designed to meet the increasing
demand for three-to-nine-ton trucks, particularly in Japan, ASEAN,
Latin America and other emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
Daimler Chairman Juergen Schrempp said the accord, a part of
Daimler's Asia strategy, is important for his company to expand
the commercial vehicle business in the eastern hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, the Stuttgart-based company said the
cooperation marked the start for a long-term partnership, which
would offer it "new and profitable growth opportunities in a very
attractive market segment."
</P>
<P>
Earlier press reports said the cooperation negotiations could
lead Daimler to buy a stake in Nissan Diesel, a unit specializing
in trucks and buses under Japan's second largest auto manufacturer
Nissan Motor. 
</P>
