<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Natural Disasters Kill 2,571 People in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 27 (Xinhua) -- A total of 2,571 people have lost
their lives in various natural disasters that hit China in the
first half of the year, the Ministry of Civil Affairs said today.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that by 26 this month, natural disasters had
afflicted 280 million people in China, among whom some 17.23
million were once cut off from the outside world by the floods.
</P>
<P>
The disasters also destroyed some 3.85 million houses and
harmed the growth of 28.41 million hectares of crops, causing
direct economic losses estimated at 153.1 billion yuan (about 19
billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Civil Affairs, which takes charge of China's
disaster relief, said that this year a variety of natural
disasters, flooding in particular, frequented many parts of the
country, and that the situation was worse than in the same period
over the previous years.
</P>
<P>
In the past several months, disasters ranging from blizzards,
hailstones and frosts to earthquakes, rainstorms and floods have
been reported from many areas across the country.
</P>
<P>
From mid June to early July, a dozen provinces and autonomous
regions south of the Yangtze River, including Jiangxi, Hunan,
Hubei, Fujian, Guangdong and Guangxi, were stricken by serious
flooding caused by unusual heavy rains. Some of them now remain
under the serious threat of new and greater floods as the Yangtze
seems to be reaching the peak of its high-water season.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Civil Affairs said that relevant departments of
the central government have to date allocated 1.58 billion yuan
(about 195 million US dollars) for disaster relief across the
country.
</P>
<P>
By July 26, the ministry had also received 17.82 million yuan
and materials worth 22.45 million yuan in domestic and foreign
donations for disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
All the donated relief materials have been distributed to the
needy people in the disaster-stricken regions according to their
donors' wishes, said the ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 11:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PLO Official Concerned About Egyptian-French </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian official Monday
voiced his concern about the fate of the French-Egyptian
initiative aimed at advancing the Mideast peace process, saying
that Israeli intransigency will stumble the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Farouk Kaddoumi, director of the Political Department of the
Palestine Liberation Organization made the remarks after a meeting
with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa at the Cairo
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
The two officials discussed the Egyptian-French initiative and
the coming meeting of Al-Qods (Jerusalem) Committee of the
Organization of Islamic Conference to be held in Casablanca,
Morocco, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The initiative calling for an international conference to
salvage the stalled Mideast peace process was raised in May during
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's visit to Paris.
</P>
<P>
When asked if he is hopeful that the initiative would help move
forward the peace process, Kaddoumi said "it is an attempt, but
the current Israeli stance will foil everything."
</P>
<P>
"There are numerous attempts to revive the stalemated peace
march but as long as Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
remains in power all those attempts will be in vain," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that the deadlocked peace march has almost come
to "a dead end."
</P>
<P>
Kaddoumi made a stopover here en route to Tunisia from Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
After the morning meeting, Moussa left for Paris for a two-day
visit to discuss with his French counterpart Hubert Vedrine the
details of the French-Egyptian initiative.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been deadlocked for 16
months due to Israel's move to build Jewish settlements in the
Arab East Jerusalem and its intransigent position on redeployment
from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The proposal is widely seen as a way to get the peace process
back on track.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
