<HEADLINE> Jordan: Israel Demolishes 68 Arab Homes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Israelis have demolished 68
Arab homes in the occupied West Bank and Arab East Jerusalem since
the beginning of this year, three times higher than the number for
the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The figures were contained in a Jordanian government report on
Israel's illegal measures and inhuman practices in territories
under its control. The report was handed over Sunday by the
Jordanian Department of Palestinian Affairs to a visiting
U.N. team probing Israel's human rights violation activities in
the occupied Palestinian lands.
</P>
<P>
Israel is continuing its drive to demolish Arab homes, expand
and establish Jewish settlements on the Palestinian lands and
repress Palestinian civilians, said the report which was obtained
by Xinhua here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some 320,000 Israelis have settled in the Gaza
Strip and the West Bank, including the Arab East Jerusalem since
1967, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report also included other details about Israel's
confiscation of Arab land, construction of Jewish settlements,
closure of occupied Arab territories and the expansion of
Jerusalem's boundaries.
</P>
<P>
In the report, the department also reviewed Jordan's policy of
supporting the Palestinians while the Middle East peace process is
retreating as a result of Israel's hard-line policy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, John de Saram, head of the three-member U.N. mission
and Sri Lanka's ambassador to the U.N., said that Jordan's report
constitutes an important reference on which the mission will base
its report for the U.N. General Assembly, the semi-official Jordan
Times reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Saram said that the mission had visited a number of countries
in the region to collect information about the Palestinians in the
occupied Arab territories.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the Israeli government has repeatedly
refused any U.N. fact-finding team's visit to the occupied
territories.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
