<HEADLINE> Iran, Iraq Agrees on Joint Efforts on MIAs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Iranian and Iraqi officials agreed
on Monday to continue their joint efforts to search for those
missing in actions (MIA) during the 1980-88 war between the two
countries, Tehran radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached in Abadan, Iran's border province of
Khuzestan at a meeting between head of Iran's committee in charge
of searching for MIAs Mir Feisal Baqerzadeh and his unnamed Iraqi
counterpart.
</P>
<P>
The two countries agreed to exchange on Tuesday the remains of
some Iranian and Iraqi soldiers killed during the war, the report
said. No figure was given about the exchange.
</P>
<P>
In May, the two former enemies started their joint search for
the remains of dead soldiers close to their common borders and the
two sides exchanged the remains of 53 Iranians and 134 Iraqis last
month.
</P>
<P>
Tehran and Baghdad have agreed to speed up their efforts to
solve the issues of MIAs and prisoners of war (POW), which are the
main hurdles for the normalization of the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Iranian officials recently announced that Iran and Iraq could
close the files of POWs within six months as the two sides showed
their sincerity in solving their issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
