<HEADLINE> Four British Cabinet Ministers Sacked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 27 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
sacked four ministers on Monday in the first reshuffle of his
cabinet since the Labor Party won a landslide victory in the
general elections in May last year.
</P>
<P>
The BBC reported the four sacked ministers were Social Security
Secretary Harriet Harman, Transport Secretary Gavin Strang, Public
Services Secretary David Clark and Lord Ivor Richard, leader of
the House of Lords.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Baroness Margaret Jay, a junior health minister,
would replace Richard in the House of Lords.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Minister Jack Cunningham is expected to get a new
role as "Whitehall enforcer." He will coordinate policy throughout
government departments.
</P>
<P>
Major ministers, such as Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon
Brown, Home Secretary or interior minister Jack Straw, Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook, and Education Secretary David Blunkett are
expected to remain at their jobs.
</P>
<P>
Blair's team has been unchanged since Labor's win last year
ended 18 years of conservative rule in the country. Political
sources said the reshuffle was an opportunity for Blair to put his
personal stamp on the cabinet. 
</P>
