<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smart Partnership Crucial for Southern Africa: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Smart partnerships were crucial
for the economic development in southern Africa and would help redress
its many problems, South African Press Association (SAPA) Monday
quoted Namibian President Sam Nujoma as saying.
</P>
<P>
Nujoma was speaking Sunday night at a banquet for Southern African
Development Community (SADC) heads of state who are attending the
second Southern African International Dialog (SAID) in the Namibian
coastal town of Swakopmund.
</P>
<P>
"This impressive gathering is a reaffirmation of our commitment to
both the philosophy and practice of smart partnerships as a way of
engendering sufficient trust among different players in the process of
socio-economic development and wealth generation," Nujoma said.
</P>
<P>
"All parties to a smart partnership must recognize that their
success is inextricably intertwined with the success of their partners
and that the failure of one can lead to the failure of all.
</P>
<P>
"There can be no doubt that the increased reliance on smart
partnership will improve relationships between governments and the
private sector, between employers and their employees, and between
suppliers and customers," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nujoma said cooperative working relationships were essential
in promoting trust among the different commercial players, adding
that smart partnership could best be achieved by networking at
the human level and by regular face-to-face contact to resolve
problems.
</P>
<P>
With recent regional achievements, including Namibia's
independence eight years ago, the end of South Africa's
white-minority rule in 1994 and the transformation of the
Southern African Development Coordinating Conference into the
SADC, Nujoma said, the region became a focus of attention as an
attractive emerging market.
</P>
<P>
The world began to look favorably to the region as an area
with bright prospects for increased growth in productivity,
trade, tourism and financial services, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Nujoma said with these fundamental changes, southern Africa
had, by and large, come to enjoy peace and stability and these
factors had increased attraction to the enormity of its natural
resources.
</P>
<P>
"However, before the region and this continent can fully
realize their economic potential, we must work hard to overcome
the legacy of our past which was marked by racial tensions,
violence and unjust socio-economic relations," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This legacy left us with a number of limiting factors, such
as a very limited pool of skilled human resources and
institutional capacity as well as a certain degree of mistrust,
which put brakes on our drive toward development and economic
growth."
</P>
<P>
The SAID, which began Sunday, is being attended by the SADC
leaders and 350 representatives of labor and business in the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Opens New National Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has opened a new national
park, the Cross River National Park, to tourists after 10 years
of development, This Day newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report said the park, located in the Cross River State in
southeastern Nigeria, protects one of the undisturbed tropical
forests in the west African country. It is also the home of many
species of plants, birds, butterflies, fish and animals.
</P>
<P>
Some of the wild life in the park, such as the drill,
angwantibo, preusss guenon, the red-headed rock-fowl,
white-throated babbler, green bush shrike and bannerman's weaver
are endangered and not found anywhere else, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria now has about 14 national parks and reserves,
including the most famous Yankari National Park in Bauchi State
in the north. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
