<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Debt Conversion Plan Pays Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has cut its external debt
by 1.247 billion U.S. Dollars by the end of June through the Debt
Conversion Program (DCP) introduced in 1988, according to figures
from the Central Bank of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The bank said about 981.8 million U.S. Dollars of debt were
canceled through auctions organized monthly by it, while another
266.11 million U.S. Dollars were canceled outside auction.
</P>
<P>
Overseen by the Debt Conversion Committee, the program
involves the sale of an external debt instrument for a domestic
debt or equity participation in domestic enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The categories of debts which were canceled through auction
include provision notes, restructured and refinanced commercial
bank debts and Paris Club debts (debts to foreign governments).
</P>
<P>
In the past decade, a total of 165.3 million U.S. Dollars in
commercial bank debts were canceled through auction, while
another 64.14 million U.S. Dollars wiped out outside auction.
</P>
<P>
A total of 48.2 million U.S. Dollars in Paris Club debt were
removed through auction, with another 2.41 million U.S. Dollars
written off outside it.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's new military leader, General Abdulsalam Abubakar
promised last week to liberalize the DCP to encourage further
foreign participation in it.
</P>
<P>
The country's external debt currently stands at about 25
billion U.S. Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
