<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Urged Less Input in Jordanian-Israeli Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Israel is considering to make
concessions to solve the investment problem concerning its only
joint industrial zone with Arabs.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government is looking into the demands by Jordanian
investors for lowering Israeli input in the products that are
manufactured in the Qualifying Industrial Zone (QIZ), the
semi-official Jordan Times reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We are studying the investors' request to lower our input to 8
percent (from 11.7 percent)," the newspaper quoted Roey Gilad, the
spokesman for the Israeli Embassy in Amman, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian investors in the Irbid QIZ, some 80 kilometers north
to Amman, earlier this month required Israel to reduce its input
in the zone to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement reached last November, which was backed by
the U.S., products from the zone can enjoy a duty-free entry into
the U.S. markets if Jordan and Israel each contributes a certain
amount of input into the exports.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, any piece of duty-free export to
the U.S. must contain 35 percent of input from the industrial zone
itself, with Jordan and Israel each paying a share of 11.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
But after the zone was designated in March, Jordanian investors
found that they invested a lot on the infrastructure in the zone,
so if the their input stays at 11.7 percent, then they might not
be able to make balance in a short time, let alone make profit for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
Omar Salah, chairman of the Century Investment Group which
owns most of the manufacturing projects in the zone, said that the
11.7 percent input was agreed on only by the government, but the
investors have to make their own calculations.
</P>
<P>
The increase of Jordan's input will get more Jordanians
employed in the zone and help the Jordanian investors harvest
profit in a relatively short term, Salah said.
</P>
<P>
Salah was confident that Israel will cooperate and agree to
lower its input.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. trade department also supports the initiative of
lowering the (Israeli) percentage in order to encourage more
investments in Jordan," Salah said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. trade department has been surprised by the fact that
no Jordanian investors in the zone have applied for duty-free
entry to the U.S. markets since March.
</P>
<P>
He expected the problem to have been solved by October when a
U.S. official from the Department of Commercial Affairs visits the
region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Jordanian government also voiced its support for
the investors on the cut request.
</P>
<P>
The agreement to build a joint zone was signed to make Jordan
share the economic dividends resulting from the 1994 peace deal
between Israel and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Jordan had no direct foreign investment for years and badly
needs to create jobs.
</P>
<P>
For Jordan, the QIZ deal means new markets and over 2,000
jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
