<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji Addresses Grain Marketing System Reform (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji said
recently that new efforts should be made to gain an accurate
understanding of grain purchasing and marketing policies, and
ensure that reform of the grain distribution system proceeds
smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Zhu made the remarks during a workshop held between July 23-25
to discuss the restructuring of grain marketing systems. The
workshop was designed to help solve problems arising during
implementing grain marketing policies adopted during a related
national conference held in late April.
</P>
<P>
Restructuring the grain distribution system represent a major
aspect of the central government's reform agenda for this year,
and is main task in national economic development. Restructuring
is directly related to China's reform, development and stability,
said Zhu, adding that localities and related departments should
follow set policies to the letter in a bid to achieve good results.
</P>
<P>
He criticized various areas which have deviated from grain
reform policies as "having either a poor or one-sided
understanding of the central government's guidelines".
</P>
<P>
He noted that some areas have failed to take effective steps to
manage grain purchasing markets, and have instead either created
regional boundaries, or otherwise restricted trade at rural and
urban fairs.
</P>
<P>
The premier reiterated that grain marketing system reform
should focus on "three policies": open-ended purchases of surplus
grain at government prices; marketing grain at prices which earn
related enterprises a slight profit; and, setting aside special
funds for grain purchases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji Addressed Smooth Grain Marketing System Reform (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhu elaborated on the three policies by noting that grain
enterprises should provide better services, purchase all surplus
grain farmers offer for sale, and pay cash on delivery. He said
efforts should be made to ensure that grain purchasers, both
private and individual, are prevented from setting wholesale
prices for markets above county level and in turn controlling
grain trade activities. Zhu also called for a strict ban on
regional boundaries.
</P>
<P>
State-owned grain firms must observe the policy to selling
grain at prices which allow for minimum profits and no new losses
will be allowed in the process. Nongovernment grain enterprises
will be permitted to determine their own sales prices.
</P>
<P>
The Agricultural Development Bank should closely supervise the
management of grain purchase funds. Financial departments, on the
other hand, should secure timely and adequate provision of capital
for grain purchases.
</P>
<P>
Zhu also called on local governments and law enforcement
departments to deal harshly with violations of grain policies,
regardless of those involved in related cases.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, everything possible must be done to provide
more grain storage capacity and protect related facilities,
especially during the flood season.
</P>
<P>
The workshop was attended by leaders from major grain
production provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions,
officials in charge of grain production, and leading officials
from related central and provincial departments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0093 </DOCNO>
