<HEADLINE> State Of Emergency Declared In Eastern China Because Of Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, July 27 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province
declared a state of emergency today in accordance with the
Anti-Flood Law because of rising water levels on the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The water level at Datong Measuring Station was quickly
approaching 10 m, only 0.2 m lower than the record level in 1954,
and the rate of flow was 79,200 cubic meters per second.
</P>
<P>
Analysts predict that the record will be broken in the next few
days and the provincial government has asked localities to do
their utmost to protect the embankments of the Yangtze and
cities and people along the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
Eight teams have been sent by the provincial government to take
part in the flood-relief work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
