<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Child's Illustrations of Masterpiece Discovered in France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Some 20 illustrations by a
12-year-old girl in 1933 on the masterpiece of French writer
Louis-Ferdinand Celine, "Trip to the End of the Night," have been
discovered, Le Figaro reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Eliane Bonabel told the daily she first saw Celine when she
went to have a medical consultation in the clinic of the writer,
who was also a famous doctor in Paris in the 1930s and 1940s.
</P>
<P>
Bonabel said that Celine asked her to draw a picture for him,
and the doctor-writer was impressed by the talent of the young
girl and entrusted her with the work of illustrating his works
later.
</P>
<P>
Asked how she could do it when she was only 12, Bonabel said
she imagined New York, which was depicted by Celine in the novel
as Paris, where she grew up.
</P>
<P>
She said the part on the colonial life in Africa fascinated
her, because there had been one year earlier a World Exhibition in
 Paris which displayed colonial trophies of Europe from Africa and
 other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
As for the scenes of wars, she said her generation was fully
"nourished by the tales of war."
</P>
<P>
"Trip to the End of the Night" remains one of the most popular
novels in France, while the author, who died in 1961, is
considered the most controversial figure of 20th century French
literature. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sir Edward Youde Memorial Fund for 1998-99 Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 27 (Xinhua) -- A total of 12 Hong Kong students
have won awards under the Sir Edward Youde Memorial Fund this year
to pursue their overseas postgraduate and undergraduate studies,
the fund's council said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Sir Edward Youde Memorial Fund was established in 1987 with
public donations to commemorate the late Hong Kong Governor Sir
Edward Youde. The purpose of the fund is to provide for and
encourage the education or learning of, or research by, the people
of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Since 1988, a total of 47 fellows and 58 scholars, including
four disabled students have benefited from the fund to pursue
higher learning overseas. 
