<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Level on Dongting Lake Reaches All-time High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The flood situation of the
Dongting Lake area in central China's Hunan Province is worsening,
as the water level at the lake's Chenglingji Hydrological Station
had surpassed the historical record of 35.31 meters to stand at
35.48 meters by 8:00 this morning.
</P>
<P>
The water level, whose danger stage is 32 meters and all-time
high was registered in 1996, is still on the rise. It grew by 0.17
meters in the past 24 hours, with a flow rate of 34,100
cu.m./second, according to the provincial flood control
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The rise was caused by torrential rains in neighboring areas on
Sunday. Of the 134 protective embankments in the lake area, 124
are at emergency water level, and 109 at danger level.
</P>
<P>
Some 1.7 million people are involved in fighting the flood. The
provincial Party secretary and governor also came to
flood-threatened Yueyang city and Changde city, respectively,
leading flood control efforts.
</P>
<P>
Huarong County has taken steps to secure the section of the
Beijing-Guangzhou Railway and the National 107 Expressway. Yueyang
is making all efforts to safeguard 27 protective embankments of
more than 660 hectares each.  
</P>
</TEXT>
