<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali PM Leaves for Colombo to Attend SAARC Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Girija
Prasad Koirala left here Monday for Colombo, capital of Sri Lanka,
to attend the 10th summit of the South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation (SAARC) starting there Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He told the press Monday morning before his departure that at
the three-day summit, Nepal will give priority to poverty
alleviation, environment conservation, control of girl trafficking
and development of communication.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that cooperation and understanding between India
and Pakistan is necessary to forward the SAARC activities.
</P>
<P>
Koirala said that if the two powers have the same attitude, the
SAARC Preferential Trading Arrangement (SAPTA) can be very
fruitful and beneficial to the smaller member countries.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of trade negotiations have been completed under
SAPTA operational since December 1995, offering over 2,000 items
of products for preferential treatment in the seven member states
-- Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and
Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Exclusively special and more favorable treatment are offered to
Bangladesh, Bhutan, the Maldives and Nepal, the four least
developed countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
But the third round of talks, which should have ended in
January this year, has been postponed four times.
</P>
<P>
Koirala said that though Bhutanese King Jigme Singye Wangchuck
will not attend the summit, he will discuss the refugee issue with
Jigme Thinley, chairman of the Bhutanese Council of Ministers who
will be present at the summit.
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 Bhutanese refugees are staying in eight U.N.-run
camps in eastern Nepal after being forced to flee Bhutan in 1989
and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Seven rounds of ministerial talks between the two Himalayan
kingdoms have failed to produce any result. India has refused to
get involved in the matter, saying it is a bilateral issue.
</P>
<P>
Koirala said that he will also have talks with his Indian
counterpart Atal Bihari Vajpayee on the sidelines of the summit
about the refugee issue, the Kalapani issue and other bilateral
issues.
</P>
<P>
"We have historical documents and maps which show that Kalapani
is Nepal's land," he said. "This problem should be resolved
through bilateral talks."
</P>
<P>
"Attitude of India is positive on Kalapani issue," he added.
Kalapani is in far-western Nepal which borders India.
</P>
<P>
He said that he will also meet his Bangladeshi counterpart
Sheikh Hasina over transit trade and economic cooperation between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
And his talks with Sri Lankan President Chandrika Kumaratunga
will focus on the provision of scholarship to Nepalese students in
Ayurpedic, a traditional Nepalese medical treatment, the prime
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, bilateral talks will be held on starting air service
from Kathmandu to Bangladesh, Sri Lanka and the Maldives, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali Foreign Ministry said that the prime minister will
pay a short private visit to Singapore on way back to Kathmandu
after attending the summit.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to return home on August 3, the ministry said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
