<HEADLINE> 43,000 Killed in India's Highway Mishaps in 1995-97 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- India's Minister of State for
Surface Transport Debendra Pradhan said Monday that over 43,000
persons were killed in 140,037 accidents on the national highways
of the country during 1995-97.
</P>
<P>
In a written reply to questions in the ongoing session of the
Lower House of Parliament here, he said that altogether 158,181
people were also injured in these accidents.
</P>
<P>
In view of the increasing number of accidents on the national
highways, the government has taken a number of steps such as
widening the highways to reduce accidents, he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the highway projects, the minister of state said
that 19 projects covering about 968 km of national highways, three
projects in state highways and five in four ports were under
implementation with loan assistance from the World bank, the Asian
Development Band and Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund of Japan.
</P>
<P>
Some projects were delayed because of delay in completing land
acquisition, shifting utilities, environmental clearance, etc. he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
