<HEADLINE> Singapore Stock Market Ends Marginally Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Share prices dipped marginally
on the Singapore Stock Market Monday as the benchmark Straits
Times Industrial Index (STII) shed 2.55 points to close at
1,067.81 points.
</P>
<P>
The total turnover was 128.43 million shares, valued at 234.42
million Singapore dollars (about 136.29 million U.S. dollars).
There were 197 losers against 71 gainers while 319 counters
remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Mid-Cont remained the most active stock as it surged on a
turnover of 20.32 million units. It was followed by ST Cap that
had 19.23 million counters done. OCBC F was next with 5.61
million shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
DBS F was the top gainer of the day as it gained 60 cents to
close at 10.10 Singapore dollars resulting from its acquisition of
the PosBank. Thai Pr edged up 28 cents to end at 3.20 U.S.
dollars. Mid-Cont was up 22 cents to finish at 0.77 Singapore
dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Creative 50 continued to be the biggest loser
as it sank by 30 cents to close at 19.00 Singapore dollars. GP Bat
and UOB shed 12 cents to end at 3.16 Singapore dollars
respectively. Datacrft was down 10 cents to finish at 2.60
Singapore dollars, becoming the fourth loser of the day.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said shares closed marginally lower reversing earlier
gains as no fresh positive leads to drive the prices higher.
</P>
<P>
They said the excitement stirred up by the merger of two local
major banks, the DBS Bank and POSBank, failed to spill over to the
broader market although shares of DBS firmed from the start of the
day's trading.
</P>
<P>
Commentators noted concerns about the economic situation in
Japan and losses in Malaysian shares prevailed over the market,
dampening buying sentiment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
