<HEADLINE> East China Province on Alert of Flood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- East China's Anhui Province
announced today that it has been put on alert of flood emergency
and the anti-flood work has been given top priority on local
governments' agenda.
</P>
<P>
The province, located on the lower reach of the Yangtze River,
has been hit by torrential rains since late June. Water level at
the Anqing section of the river reached 18.13 metres at 8:00 am
today, 2.05 metres higher than the warning level.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 200 emergency cases have been spotted along
the dikes throughout Anhui. Although the cases have been dealt
with, situation there has remained tough.
</P>
<P>
Local flood-control officials forecast that the water level at
the Anqing section will reach 18.5 metres in three days, the
highest level since 1954.
</P>
<P>
At present, about 600,000 people are busy working along the
river to protect the dikes and 800 army men have been standing by
in case of emergency, according to the provincial
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
