<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia, U.S. to Hold Ministerial Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Asian economic crisis,
nuclear tests by Pakistan and India and political upheaval in
Indonesia would be top on the agenda of this week's
Australia-United States Ministerial (AUSMIN) talks in Sydney,
Australian officials said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
During a background briefing on July 31 talks, Australian
officials, who declined to be named, described the annual talks as
the most important meeting between Australia and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The United States will be represented by Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and Defense Secretary William Cohen, and
Australia's delegation will be led by Foreign Minister Alexander
Downer and Defense Minister Ian McLachlan.
</P>
<P>
The Australian officials said, "AUSMIN this year will take
place against a very different regional environment to that which
formed the context of our discussions last year."
</P>
<P>
"Obviously those changes - the Asian economic crisis and the
nuclear testing by India and Pakistan - bring a very changed
situation to our discussions," they noted.
</P>
<P>
"We'll be meeting against some fairly major dramatic events
that have taken place that would affect ... the security and the
economic stability of the (Asia-Pacific) region," they stressed.
</P>
<P>
The officials said the talks would have four key topics, such
as Asia-Pacific challenges and opportunities, global security and
political cooperation, defense cooperation and arrangements and
trade and economic arrangements and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"Australia needs to work together with the United States and
the countries of the region, both bilaterally and in international
organizations, to help meet the challenges that have become
apparent in the region," the officials said.
</P>
<P>
A communique is expected to come out of the talks, which would
restate the commitment of both sides to a close defense and
foreign policy relationship, according to the officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
