<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Welcomes US to Change MFN into NTR: FM Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministry Spokesman Tang
Guoqiang said here today that China welcomes the United States'
recent decision to change the "Most Favored Nation" (MFN) trading
status into "Normal Trade Relations" (NTR).
</P>
<P>
Tang said: "we have noticed that President Clinton has recently
signed a bill in which MFN has been changed into NTR. It is a wise
and practical move.
</P>
<P>
"By MFN, it actually means a non-discriminatory trading status
mutually granted by the U.S. and other countries on a reciprocal
basis.
</P>
<P>
"It is normal trade relations in a real sense, and by no means
a preferential trading status granted by the U.S. to other
countries, still less a special favor unilaterally given by one
side. Therefore, this change has simply restored its true meaning,
which we welcome."
</P>
<P>
However, he noted, regretfully, the U.S. has not yet given up
its practice of annual review of the trade arrangement between
China and the U.S. This discriminatory practice has not only added
a destabilizing factor to the bilateral economic relations and
trade, but is also detrimental to the smooth development of
China-U.S. relations as a whole.
</P>
<P>
China hopes the U.S. side will proceed from the fundamental
interests and the common aspiration of the people in both China
and the U.S., and put an early end to its annual review of the
normal trade relations between the two countries, so as to
facilitate a sound, stable and sustained growth for the economic
cooperation and trade between China and the U.S. and their
bilateral relations, the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
