<BODY>
<HEADLINE> LRA Rejects UN Official's Peace Initiative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's Lord's Resistance Army
(LRA) rebels have rejected the involvement of United Nations'
Ambassador for Children in Conflict Olara Otunu to end the
12-year-long insurgency in norther part of the country.
</P>
<P>
In a strongly-worded press release issued Sunday, LRA spokesman
Ladit Balgara warned the U.N. official against ignoring the
political leadership of the LRA, the New Vision daily reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"As long as he ignores the political leadership of the LRA and
tries to approach the combatants to confuse and distract them
from normal duties, he will be met in heaven," the spokesman was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He asserted that no peace agreement will be signed "without
the freedom of our people from concentration camps and from
Article 269 of the Constitution of 1995."
</P>
<P>
This article in the Constitution is said to suspend political
party activities which may interfere with the Movement government
until Parliament enacts appropriate laws.
</P>
<P>
The rebels also accusing Otunu of having his position in the
1985 Nairobi peace talks between the Tito Okello regime and
Yoweri Museveni, which they claimed brought misery and anguish to
the Acholi.
</P>
<P>
The LRA is not a charity organization, but a political rebel
force ready to face Museveni who should openly declare that he
wants talks, the press release added.
</P>
<P>
Otunu recently met with some members of Parliament, civic and
opinion leaders who attended the London Kacoke Madit (grand
conference on Uganda) and promised to go to Sudan to meet
Sudanese government officials and LRA leaders to secure the
release of abducted children.
</P>
<P>
President Museveni recently wrote to LRA leaders for peace
negotiations so as "not to block the way to peace talks" as he
said at a press conference. But there has been no publicized
response to the letter from the rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
