<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 08:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan to Adhere to Normalization of Ties With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Jordan will reject
calls to halt normalization of its ties with Israel, but will seek
a unified Arab stand on Jerusalem at an upcoming Islamic
conference, said the semi-official Jordan Times Monday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister for Development Affairs and Minister of
Foreign Affairs Jawad Anani will represent Jordan at the meeting
of the Jerusalem Committee under the Organization of Islamic
Conference (OIC), which is scheduled for July 29 to 30 in Morocco.
</P>
<P>
"The relationship between Jordan and Israel is not the same as
the relationship between Syria and Israel," Anani told the paper,
referring to the 1994 Jordanian-Israeli peace treaty and the
continued state of enmity between Damascus and Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming conference should reflect the political realities
of each country, Anani added.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper report also said Syria will use the conference to
push for an end to the Arab normalization process with
Israel. Syrian officials have targeted Jordan over its ties with
the Jewish state, urging Amman to sever these links.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Anani told the newspaper that Jordan will seek a
unified Arab stand to safeguard the current status of the Holy
City of Jerusalem in the upcoming conference.
</P>
<P>
Jordan will play its role in preserving the Muslim holy sites
in Jerusalem, he added.
</P>
<P>
The conference in Morocco comes at a particularly crucial time
in the 16-month-old deadlock in the peace process. Israel has so
far refused to accept a U.S. peace proposal to revive the peace
process on the Israeli-Palestinian track.
</P>
<P>
Israel's announcement last month to extend the boundaries of
Jerusalem has also added to the troubles of the faltering peace
process. It is widely believed in the Arab and Muslim world that
Israel is trying to change the identity of the Holy City.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is one of the two Arab countries that signed a peace
treaty with Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
