<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Approves More Fund for Oil Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
approved an additional 300 million U.S. Dollars cash call budget
for its oil industry in 1998, bringing the total investment in
the oil sector by government to 2.8 billion Dollars.
</P>
<P>
A report by "This Day" newspaper said the approval came after
a series of negotiations between the Nigerian government and
major oil operators in the country.
</P>
<P>
Oil production in Nigeria, a major world oil producer with a
daily production of over two million barrels, is done through
joint ventures between the Nigerian National Petroleum
Corporation (NNPC) and foreign oil firms including Shell, Mobil,
Chevron, Elf, Agip and Texaco.
</P>
<P>
In the last few years, these joint ventures have been forced
to scale down their exploration and production plans due to the
inability of the Nigerian government to fund its 60 percent
ownership.
</P>
<P>
From 1995 to 1997, the government's annual budget for the oil
industry had been kept at 2.05 billion Dollars. This caused harsh
criticism from both the oil and public sectors, accusing the
government of neglecting the oil sector, which provides more than
70 percent of the government's revenue and over 90 percent of the
country's foreign currency income.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the government approved a budget of 2.5 billion
Dollars, compared with the 3.5 billion Dollars as proposed by the
oil firms.
</P>
<P>
Upon his succession to Abacha in June, General Abubakar has
promised to invest more in the oil industry.
</P>
<P>
Only recently, he has ordered the immediate payment of 630
million Dollars to the oil firms as arrears owed to them by the
Abacha administration.
</P>
<P>
According to the report by "This Day", Abubakar has also
ordered the immediate payment of 175 million Dollars to oil firms
as the arrears in the first seven months of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
