<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 09:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Softens Terms on Key Sticking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Israel has softened its terms on
a key sticking point of their talks with the Palestinians over
the second stage of Israeli withdrawals from the West Bank,
Israeli newspaper Haaretz reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, while meeting
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) Deputy Chairman Mahmoud Abbas
last Saturday night, proposed that part of the West Bank to be
handed over to the Palestinians will be contiguous areas located
in the Judean Desert, and the PNA will be responsible for public
order, the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz quoted "sources close to the negotiations" as saying
that Mordechai did not specify the scope of the land in question
in the secret meeting, but it was widely believed to be 3 percent
from the 13.1 percent areas proposed to be handed over to the
Palestinians under an American initiative.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper described Mordechai's position as "significant,"
noting that it was the first time that Israel had indicated that
its withdrawal will include at least a slice of the Judean Desert.
</P>
<P>
Israeli National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon has
opposed yielding any territory in the Judean Desert, which was
near the Dead Sea, claiming that Israel needs the entire area for
security.
</P>
<P>
A second significance, Haaretz said, was that Israel accepted
Palestinian demands for the land to be contiguous. The third
Israeli concession was the agreement that the Palestinians be
responsible for public order in the area, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai also made clear at the meeting that he thought
Israel and the PNA "would not have difficulty in reaching a
compromise" on the other key sticking point -- finding the body
that would ratify the revision of the Palestinian Charter that
calls for the destruction of Israel, Haaretz said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plunge in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Share prices tumbled across the board in
Tokyo Monday with the key Nikkei index closing below 16,000 for the
first time since June 30.
</P>
<P>
A big fall in banking shares, predicated on investor worries about
who will become finance minister in the incoming government headed by
Keizo Obuchi, pulled stocks in other sectors down as well, traders
said.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange plummeted 417.53 points, or 2.55
percent, from last Friday's close to end at 15,944.36.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, lost 24.03 points or 1.91 percent to 1,233.98.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section fell to an estimated 360 million
shares from 401.44 million shares Friday.
</P>
<P>
Kawai Musical Instruments Mfg. was the day's most heavily traded
issue.
</P>
<P>
As expected by many traders, the Nikkei fell below 16,000 as market
players wait for Japan to take bold steps to cut income taxes and
rescue banks from the massive nonperforming loans they made.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi, who won last Friday's Liberal Democratic Party presidential
election, is slated to replace Ryutaro Hashimoto as prime minister and
form a cabinet Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,332 issues listed on the First Section, losers outweighed
gainers 949 to 218, with 125 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar climbed above 142
yen as the Japanese currency was weighed down by the country's
uncertain political situation.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was quoted at 142.33-36 yen at 5 p.m. (local time) after
hitting a high of 142.45 yen during the day, up from 141.61-63 yen at
9 a.m. in Tokyo and from 141.60-70 yen late Friday in New York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
