<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia, World Bank Launch Industrial Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government and the
World Bank has formally launched a Multi-purpose Credit Facility
(MCF) with an estimated value of 40 million U.S. Dollars for the
country's industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
About 30 million U.S. Dollars will be employed under the
medium-term Investment Credit Facility (ICF) to finance new
investment for conversion into fixed assets for the private
sector, according to the latest issue of the Zambia Association
of Manufacturers ZAM News available here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The balance of 10 million U.S. Dollars will be used for
short-term pre-shipment export facility aimed at financing the
exporters as working capitals.
</P>
<P>
The investors in the newly-privatized companies can make use
of the ICF funds to finance modernization and expansion projects.
While the MCF, launched recently through the Ministry of
Commerce, Trade and Industry, will provide medium-term lines of
credit to the financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The ICF loans will be based on the maturity of three to seven
years with a possible grace period of 6-17 months, both
determined by the financial institutions, while the maximum loans
will be three million U.S. Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
