<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Restructuring Sparks University Reshuffling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 27 (Xinhua) -- This year's reorganization or
elimination of a number of State Council commissions and
ministries will place a large number of colleges and universities
in the hands of local governments.
</P>
<P>
Addressing today's press conference, Vice-Minister of Education
Zhou Yuanqing said that more than 160 institutions of higher
learning are expected to be closed, merged or handed over to local
governments by September.
</P>
<P>
The institutions were formerly operated by nine ministries and
commissions, including the ministries of machine-building
industry, metallurgical industry and internal trade. The
ministries were on the State Council list of dozens of departments
eliminated earlier this year during institutional restructuring
designed to streamline and invigorate the government.
</P>
<P>
The vast majority of ministries created their own systems based
on the Soviet Model beginning in the early 1950s, and ensuing
redundant operations created surplus construction and wasted
resources. Most ministries operated dozens of small universities
which could have easily been combined into a single comprehensive
institution like Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said the new move will further promote the ongoing reform
of higher education, and that the universities will be required
to readjust their goals and better serve the nation's economic and
social needs in order to survive.
</P>
<P>
A total of 26 provinces and cities will assume or "take over"
operational responsibilities for related institutions. The
reshuffling will involve a number of complex problems in areas
such as funding, transferrals of staff records and continuation of
teaching and research programs. Experts acknowledge that the
greater influence might emerge in the psychological sphere since
most teachers and students will feel somewhat uneasy when their
universities are degraded from the state to the local level.
</P>
<P>
However, Ji Baocheng, director of the Planning Department of
the Education Ministry, said that everything has proceeded
smoothly since the readjustment was properly designed and has been
carried out under the direction of top leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese ministries and commissions have set up more than
300 universities and colleges over the years, with the future of a
number of institutions to be determined at a later date, according
to sources from the ministry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Projections Indicate Drop in Automotive Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 27 (Xinhua) -- China's third quarter automotive
output is expected to slump by 16.7 percent on second quarter
levels.
</P>
<P>
The Automotive Industry Development Institute forecasts that the
total automobile output will reach 387,965 units during the
July-September period.
</P>
<P>
However, the output of sedans will remain at 143,502 units, or
slightly lower than the 145,919 units produced in the April-June
period.
</P>
<P>
Industrial experts note that the declining trend in automotive
output is the result of slack market demand and the rising
stockpiles for a number of manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
China produced 824,700 automobiles in the first half this year,
up a mere 0.6 percent on a year-by-year basis.
</P>
<P>
The total automobile output for the year is expected to end at
between 1.65-1.7 million units. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
