<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alaska Military Commander Killed in Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The commander of all military
forces in Alaska was killed Sunday in a private plane crash, said
reports reaching here in the evening. His passenger also died.
</P>
<P>
Lieutenant general David J. McCloud was flying his YAK-54, a
single-engine, aerobatic plane Sunday when it took off from
Elmendorf Air Force Base and crashed in a paratrooper drop zone at
Fort Richardson, just east of Anchorage.
</P>
<P>
The cause of the crash was not known and the National
Transportation Safety Board was investigating.
</P>
<P>
As commander of the Alaskan command, McCloud was responsible
for more than 21,000 active duty and reserve members of U.S. Army,
Air Force, Navy and Alaska National Guard.
</P>
<P>
Air Force records indicated that he had flown many of the
aircraft types, including the B1-B bomber and most of the fighter
models used by the U.S. Air Forces during the past three decades.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Urges India, Pakistan to Sign Nuclear Treaties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Austrian Vice Chancellor Wolfgang
Schussel, on behalf of the European Union (EU), appealed anew
Tuesday India and Pakistan to refrain from any further nuclear
tests and to sign the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT).
</P>
<P>
"I reiterate the appeal to India and to Pakistan to refrain
from any further nuclear tests, to sign and move to ratify the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty as it stands and to accede to the
Non-Proliferation Treaty," Schussel told the 5th ASEAN Regional
Forum (ARF).
</P>
<P>
Schussel is attending the one-day ASEAN (Association of
Southeast Asian Nations) Regional Forum which opened here Tuesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
Schussel said the nuclear tests conducted by India and Pakistan
"pose a grave threat to international peace and security, and
constitute a serious set-back to global efforts towards nuclear
non-proliferation and disarmament."
</P>
<P>
The EU urged India and Pakistan, the two rival countries, to
contribute actively to securing the opening of negotiations in the
Conference on Disarmament for a treaty banning the production of
fissile materials for nuclear weapons, he said.
</P>
<P>
Schussel also called on the two countries to engage in a
dialogue and to try to build confidence rather than to remain on
the mutually disastrous path of confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Schussel, whose country is currently the rotating chairman of
the EU, said the EU is concerned about the continued increase in
military expenditure in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
Citing the rising economic difficulties of India and Pakistan
as a result of their costly nuclear and conventional military
expenditure, Schussel said the EU hopes that the overall military
spending in the region could be stabilized if not reduced in the
near future.
</P>
<P>
Schussel assured the other ARF participants that the EU is
ready to continue its substantial contribution to peace and
prevention of tension in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
The ARF was attended by the foreign ministers from the 10 ASEAN
dialogue partners and the nine ASEAN member countries, and
representatives from the two ASEAN observer states Cambodia and
Papua New Guinea.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN dialogue partners are the United States, China,
Russia, Japan, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, South Korea, India
and the EU. ASEAN groups the Philippines, Indonesia, Singapore,
Thailand, Malaysia, Vietnam, Laos, Myanmar and Brunei. 
</P>
</TEXT>
