<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Price Issue Delays AIDS Drugs for Ugandans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- New AIDS drugs, which arrived in
Uganda a month ago, will be available in the market later than
expected because their price takes more time to be decided on.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization (WHO) and UNAIDS officials
revealed recently that Glaxo Wellcome, the British firm supplying
the new drugs, has not obtained enough information about the
Ugandan market and, therefore, the setting of the price is
delayed, the East African weekly reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The drugs, which arrived in the Uganda on July 7, are reported
to be able to suppress the replication of the human
immunodeficiency virus (HIV).
</P>
<P>
The bulk of Ugandan AIDS patients are longing for the drugs
because other anti-AIDS drugs available in the market cost 12
million Uganda Shillings (10,000 U.S. Dollars) per year, well
beyond the means of the ordinary Ugandans.
</P>
<P>
The price of the new drugs will be settled through
negotiations between the supplier and the Ugandan government.
</P>
<P>
Uganda was listed as one of the pilot countries for the new
drugs at the newly-concluded World's AIDS Conference.
</P>
<P>
One-tenth of the 20 million Ugandans are estimated to be HIV
positive and some 500,000 people have died of the killing disease
since the first case of AIDS was reported in 1982.
</P>
<P>
Although Uganda is no longer one of the poorest countries in
the world, a New Vision newspaper report said in May that 86
percent of Ugandan families are still living below of poverty
line of 13,380 Shillings (11 U.S. Dollars) a month and some 60
percent of these families are struggling under the absolute
poverty line of 9,470 Shillings (eight U.S. Dollars) a month.
</P>
<P>
The price of the new AIDS drugs is said to reach 9,000 Dollars
a year. So it may still be too expensive for ordinary AIDS
patients in Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Money Transfer Service Expands in East Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- A regional money transfer service
between the capital cities of Tanzania, Uganda and Kenya, has now
been extended to 119 towns within the three east African
countries.
</P>
<P>
The expansion of the Interstate Speed Cash service commenced
on July 13 to include all regional post offices and selected
district post offices, the East African weekly newspaper reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The service was launched last year within the framework of the
East African Cooperation but was restricted to general post
offices in Nairobi, Dar es Salaam and Kampala.
</P>
<P>
There are 42 post offices in Kenya, 39 in Tanzania and 38 in
Uganda will now offer the service.
</P>
<P>
The maximum period of money delivery posted from any point
within east Africa will be seven days to far flung district post
offices and three to four days to major cities, said Hugo Mvamba,
a senior official with the Tanzania Posts Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The maximum amount of money that can be sent from country to
country will be the local equivalent of 1,000 U.S. Dollars and
the minimum 10 Dollars. One person is allowed to send more than
two orders a day but the maximum should not exceed 1,000 Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources hope the expanded service will boost internal
and cross-border trade by making money transfer easier and
faster. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Launches One-Year Fixed Rate Bearer Bond </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Kenya has
launched a one-year fixed rate bearer bond for investors with at
least 10,000 Shillings or 161 U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The move is expected to reduce interest rates on Treasury
Bills and compete with commercial banks for direct cheaper
deposits, the East African weekly newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The bearer bond attracts a fixed interest rate of 16 percent
per annum and is payable quarterly.
</P>
<P>
It will take about 25 percent, or the 64 biLl=9L!llings
(1.03 billion U.S. Dollars) of the 267 billion Shillings (4.3
billion U.S. Dollars) currently invested in savings accounts of
commercial banks, which offer interest rates of less than 11
percent.
</P>
<P>
John Munge of Shah Munge &AMP; Partners Ltd. said the offer was
made through his firm and other members of the Nairobi Stock
Exchange last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Subsequent issues of the bond will be on sale at the beginning
of every month, he said.
</P>
<P>
The bond has a maturity period of one year. After that there
will be secondary trading in multiples of 10,000 Shillings at the
Nairobi Stock Exchange. 
</P>
</TEXT>
