<HEADLINE> Mkapa Urges Africans to Learn From Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa
has urged African countries to consider engaging Asia's technical
advancement to develop in the coming millennium.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa made the remarks Sunday during a brief stopover at the
Lusaka International Airport on his way to Namibia's west coastal
city of Swakopmund for the second Southern African International
Dialog (the Smart Partnership round table discussion), Zambia
Daily Mail reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa also said it is time for Africa to learn to utilize the
legislative and regulative steps which have recorded numerous
successes in most Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian president, who was met at the airport by Zambian
President Frederick Chiluba, pointed out that deregulated labor
policies in most Asian countries have contributed to the success
of the continent.
</P>
<P>
He called on the African countries to reconsider their labor
laws, saying that these should be flexible to the changing
economies in the world.
</P>
<P>
"We expect to learn much from our Asian colleagues on their
labor regulations and legislature which we may find useful in our
governments at the Smart Partnership round table talks in
Namibia," said Mkapa.
</P>
<P>
The round-table's discussions are expected to engage some
African heads of state, entrepreneurs, academics and trade
unionists with their colleagues from other parts of the world
such as Asia and Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
