<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ranariddh Expects Cambodia to Join ASEAN After Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Prince Norodom Ranariddh voiced
hope Monday that Cambodia's bid to join the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and restore its seat at the United
Nations would be boosted by Sunday election.
</P>
<P>
The self-organized, multi-party election, if successful and
accepted, would pave the way for Cambodia to rejoin the
international community, Ranariddh said in an interview with
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Millions of Cambodians went to the poll in the historic
election in the hope of giving the country a chance for peace,
stability and a legitimate government.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh, who is also one of the leading candidate in the
election, said "the international community also wants to embrace
Cambodia again not only for Cambodian interests but also for
regional stability."
</P>
<P>
He said if Cambodia remained unstable, it would not only
affect the economic development of the country itself, but also
threaten long-term stability of the region.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN refused to admit Cambodia as a new member after Ranariddh
was ousted as Cambodia's first-premier by forces loyal to
co-premier Hun Sen in July 1997. Cambodia has been absent from its
seat at the United Nations ever since.
</P>
<P>
"The Cambodian people want to see changes and have new leaders
to build a new image of Cambodia. That is why they showed great
enthusiasm for the election," Ranariddh said.
</P>
<P>
More than 90 percent of the registered voters cast their votes
Sunday, a much higher percentage than previously expected,
according to the Cambodian National Election Committee (NEC).
</P>
<P>
Judging from the registration and balloting, Ranariddh said,
the election had been "relatively free and fair."
</P>
<P>
When asked about whether he was confident that his Funcinpec
Party would win the election, Ranariddh said he would wait and see
the final results.
</P>
<P>
Funcinpec, the ruling Cambodian People's Party (CPP) and Sam
Rainsy Party were front runners in the election and hoped to
lead what most people expect will be another coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh said if Funcinpec failed in the election, it would
remain active in politics as an opposition in the National
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
"As for myself, I would never work in the new government if
it was led by the CPP," Ranariddh said. The CPP fielded Hun Sen,
its vice-president, as candidate for premiership.
</P>
<P>
The prince said if the new government was led by his party,
priorities would be given to political stability and economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Economic development should begin from the countryside where 90
percent of the Cambodians live, he said, "I would introduce
advanced technology and seek investment to develop Cambodia's
agriculture."
</P>
<P>
Funcinpec would adhere to the current foreign policy based on
independence, self-reliance and non-alignment, Ranariddh said.
</P>
<P>
"We will stick to the `one-China` policy and continue to
develop relations with China," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0163 </DOCNO>
