<HEADLINE> China Boosts Gold Tally to Six at Goodwill Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 26 (Xinhua) -- China's gymnasts Huang Xu and
Ling Jie combined to win China's sixth gold medal here Sunday in
the mixed pairs competition, while the United States claimed the
wrestling team title at the 1998 Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
Brazilians Guiberme Marques and Para Ferreira captured the
men's beach volleyball gold by beating Adam Johnson and Karch
Kiraly of the United States 12-11, 12-4.
</P>
<P>
But the host pocketed a top honor in the women's platform
diving through Laura Wilkinson.
</P>
<P>
Huang, who capped the men's parallel bars gold in the
individual gymnastics, teamed up with Ling Jie to score a total of
39.000 points in the mixed pair competition, ahead of Russia's
Alexei Nemov and Svetlana Khorkina, 38.725, and another Russian
pair Alexei Bondarenko and Anna Kovaleva, 38.7000.
</P>
<P>
"We will send this gold to Sang Lan, who injured her neck on
July 21 and paralyzed at the hospital here. We have drawn courage
from her and we knew that she was watching the competition
tonight," said Huang.
</P>
<P>
Sang Lan, 17, suffered an injury in the warm-up for the women's
vault competition on July 21, and she cannot feel anything from
mid-chest down after completing her operation yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Marques and Ferreira, who kept their matches with a record of
all wins before the final, displayed their strength by beating the
American tandem in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
They won a total of 30,000 U.S. dollars in prize money. It was
their second time to win a major title in the past 11 months on
the U.S. soil at the Central Park, Manhattan
</P>
<P>
The Brazilians, who downed Johanson and Kiraly 15-3 Thursday in
group A, won the 55 minute first set after the both sides tied at
11-all. They won the tie-break point to silence the local
supporters.
</P>
<P>
In the match determining the bronze medal, Martin Conde and
Esteban Martinez of Argentina downed Julien Prosser and Leo Zahner
of Australia 12-11 and 12-9.
</P>
<P>
Wilkinson, a little known American before the Games, upset
strong Chinese and Russian rivals in the pool, winning through
with a total of 504.21 points ahead of China's Cai Yuyan, 501.57,
and Sang Xue, 483.45.
</P>
<P>
Wilkinson led the first round with 45.000, but Sang Xue
overtook the leading position in the next and kept the top two
places firmly after the first round dives.
</P>
<P>
But the American surged ahead in the next three outings with a
series of blistering fine performances, regaining the lead in
commanding style.
</P>
<P>
Sang scored the highest score 80.19 on her seventh dive, and
Cai got a 73.26-point mark on the same round. However, Wilkinson s
ettled her triumph with a last dive worth 67.20 before Cai came
short to turn the table with a following 61.20.
</P>
<P>
The six-point difference brought the gold to the American
diver. China has chalked up four victories in diving in the past
days.
</P>
<P>
In the wrestling competition, the United States beat Russia
before winning the team title. 
</P>
</TEXT>
