<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Declines to Sign Military Accord With U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has refused to sign the
Status of Forces Agreement with the United States (SOFA), The
Finance Express daily reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a front-paged report, the newspaper said, "The Foreign
Office in a letter on Sunday communicated to the U.S. embassy the
Bangladeshi government decision not to sign the agreement."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. embassy sources confirmed the Foreign Office's
communication but declined to make any comment on Dhaka's refusal
to sign the accord, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the national news agency Bangladesh Sangbad
Sangstha (BSS) issued a report quoting a "competent source" at the
Ministry of Foreign Affairs as saying that Bangladesh was unlikely
to sign SOFA with the U.S. as "Bangladesh has nothing to gain by
signing the SOFA. Rather, it (SOFA) would be detrimental to the
national interest."
</P>
<P>
"National interest will be above everything" while entering
into any agreement with any country, big or small, on any issue,
be it on economic matters or military affairs, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Clauses providing visa-free entry for U.S. troops, unrestricted
movement for American troops in the country and the entry of
equipment and supplies carried by U.S. troops without undergoing
customs clearance were not acceptable to Bangladesh, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
Besides, as a member of the South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation (SAARC), Bangladesh had a responsibility for
the region as a whole and could not allow entry of foreign troops
into the region which might have "profound and far-reaching
consequences," it added.
</P>
<P>
Americans desirous of entering Bangladesh to carry out relief
operations, or for military exercises or for other legitimate
purposes could do so through a memorandum of understanding (MOU)
on a case-by-case basis. "We can have as many MOUs as required,"
the news agency quoted the source as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
