<HEADLINE> Zimbabweans to Study Land Redistribution in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe will send officials in
the government and farmers' unions to Brazil and Colombia before
the end of the year to study how the two countries are
implementing their land redistribution program.
</P>
<P>
The tour is jointly sponsored by the British and Danish
governments through the World Bank, the daily Herald reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, the tour comes at a time when the government has
announced that the resettlement of landless Zimbabweans has
started, making it unclear how lessons learned from the Latin
American countries would fit into an already running program.
</P>
<P>
Ruling ZANU (PF) National Chairman and National Land
Acquisition Committee Chairman Joseph Msika is expected to lead
the delegation scheduled to leave after the September Donor
Conference on Land to be held in Harare.
</P>
<P>
In an interview in Bulawayo, the country's second largest city
Sunday, Msika said the tour was proposed by the World Bank for
the ministries involved in the land redistribution program.
</P>
<P>
"It's part of an exercise to see how others have done it,"
Msika said. "There is absolutely nothing wrong with it coming at
a time when our resettlement program has started. We will simply
pick on ideas that apply to our system." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
