<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges India, Pakistan to Adhere to Nuke Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The United States Monday asked
India and Pakistan, whose nuclear tests in May touched off an
uproar across the world, to "adhere to the CTBT without
conditions."
</P>
<P>
"We ask that they not produce fissile material for nuclear
weapons pending conclusion of a treaty to halt such production
permanently," U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright told the
ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF) meeting which opened here Monday
morning.
</P>
<P>
She also urged the two countries not to deploy nuclear weapons
or missiles capable of carrying them and commit themselves to
effective means of controlling exports of dangerous weapons,
materials and technologies.
</P>
<P>
India carried out five nuclear explosions in mid-May and
Pakistan responded by setting off six nuclear devices towards the
end of that month.
</P>
<P>
Albright called on India and Pakistan, two neighbors long at
odds, to resume high-level dialogue with each other to address the
full range of issues that divide them, including Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
She expressed the hope that the prime ministers of the two
countries, who will be in Colombo, capital of Sri Lanka, to attend
a summit meeting of South Asian countries this week, "can get such
a dialogue on track."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary of state said the South Asian region had
been getting safer until India and Pakistan tested nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
"While both nations have legitimate security concerns, neither
faced an imminent threat that could justify the far greater danger
we all now face," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
