<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for New Security Approach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- China Monday called for a new
security approach and new ways to safeguard peace.
</P>
<P>
"In order to secure lasting peace and development in the
Asia-Pacific, it is necessary to nurture a new security approach
and seek new ways of safeguarding peace," Chinese Foreign Minister
Tang Jiaxuan said in an address at the ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF)
meeting, which opened here Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Tang noted that the past year has been one of continued
significant and profound changes in the Asia-Pacific region: Major
powers have further readjusted and improved their relations,
countries have strengthened dialogue and cooperation and there
have been gradually deeper-going regional multilateral economic
and security dialogue and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Peace, development and cooperation remain the main trend in the
regional situation, he declared.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that destabilizing factors have
apparently increased in the Asia-Pacific region after India and
Pakistan conducted nuclear tests in May, "plunging South Asia into
a sudden wave of tension."
</P>
<P>
As implications of the financial crisis spread, new problems
have cropped up one after another in the process of regional
development, he said. "The Cold-War mentality still has its
influence in the region. Such acts as reinforcing military
alliance and interfering in other countries' internal affairs
continue to occur."
</P>
<P>
As it stands, he added, the issues of peace and development are
far from being settled and remain the two major themes confronting
us.
</P>
<P>
He said that to develop state-to-state ties on the basis of the
Five Principles of mutual respect for sovereignty and territorial
integrity, mutual non-aggression, non-interference in each other's
internal affairs, equality and mutual benefit and peaceful
coexistence "constitutes the political foundation and prerequisite
of security at both regional and international levels."
</P>
<P>
Tang also described increasing mutual understanding and trust
through dialogue and cooperation and undertaking to settle
state-to-state disputes and conflicts through peaceful means as "a
practical way of ensuring peace and security."
</P>
<P>
"History has already proven that the security concept and
mechanism based on military alliance and achieved through the
build-up of military strength cannot make lasting peace," he said.
"In this diversified region of the Asia-Pacific, it is all the
more necessary to work to enhance mutual understanding and trust
through dialogue and cooperation."
</P>
<P>
In addition, he stressed that economic growth and common
prosperity are the material basis for regional and global
security. "In today's world when the international situation moves
toward relaxation and economic development faces a rare
opportunity, to concentrate limited resources on economic and
social development is an easier way for a country to move into the
ranks of strong nations of the world and provides a positive
guarantee for national and regional security as well."
</P>
<P>
The Chinese foreign minister pointed out that as the sole
governmental-level channel for security dialogue in the
Asia-Pacific region, the ARF is, under the new circumstances,
playing an ever-greater role in enhancing mutual confidence among
Asian-Pacific countries and promoting regional peace and
stability.
</P>
<P>
The ARF, initiated in 1993 and first convened in the following
year, is a forum for Asian-Pacific countries to discuss political
and security cooperation and security matters such as
confidence-building measures and preventive diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
Tang noted that as a permanent member of the U.N. Security
Council, China is committed to maintaining peace, stability,
development and cooperation in the Asia-Pacific region and has
fulfilled its share of responsibility and obligation both in
alleviating East Asia's financial crisis and in easing up the
tension in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
"China will, as always, participate in the multi-tiered and
multi-channeled dialogues and cooperation in the security field of
the Asia-Pacific region," he declared. "China was, is and will be
a staunch force in maintaining regional and global peace and
stability and a positive factor promoting common development."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls Economic Security Part of National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan, in an address to the ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF) here
Monday, described economic security as part of national and
regional stability.
</P>
<P>
"The East Asian financial crisis fully indicates that economic
security has increasingly become an inseparable part of national
or regional stability," Tang said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that economic security is based first of all on
formulating the right strategy for economic growth and enhancing a
country's economic might and competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
"It is based on political stability, the inviolability of
sovereignty and respect for its model of development," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he added, "it is necessary for countries to take an
active part in and work to promote regional economic cooperation
and coordination, readjust and improve the existing international
economic and financial order and, in particular, to strengthen
supervision over and take strict precautions against excessive
speculation."
</P>
<P>
Tang stressed that economic security is mutual and "it is
inadvisable to try to shift one's troubles onto others." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980727.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
