<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Exports to EU Increase 19 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dhaka, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's exports to the European
Union (EU) increased by 19 percent in value in 1997 and its
imports from the trading block grew by 11 percent with the balance
in favor of the country, The Financial Express daily reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Michael Drury, head of a European
Commission (EC) delegation, while addressing a luncheon here
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Exports of Bangladesh to the EU stood at 88 billion taka (1.87
billion U.S. dollars) while its imports from the EU were 33
billion taka (702 million dollars) in 1997 calendar year, Drury
stated.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that ready-made garments accounted for 84
percent of Bangladesh's exports to the EU in the year with a
growth of 26 percent over the previous year due to the use of the
Generalized System of Preferences (GSP) under which Bangladesh
enjoyed duty-free access to European markets.
</P>
<P>
The duty was falling in Europe with the multifiber agreement,
under which Bangladesh enjoyed protected quota, to be phased out
by the year 2005, he warned.
</P>
<P>
He called for conscious efforts to identify and create other
growth possibilities in Bangladesh with a view to employing the
low-cost labor of the country in combination with technological
improvements that ultimately increase the value of workforce.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
