<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 9 Foreign Firms to Compete for Oil, Gas Exploration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Nine foreign companies, with five of
them from the United States, will be invited for the final
negotiation for oil and gas exploration in Bangladesh, according
to Petrobangla, the state-owned agency in charge of gas and oil
exploration and production in the country.
</P>
<P>
The results of the Second Round Block Bidding for oil and gas
exploration in Bangladesh, which was announced Sunday, showed that
European companies Shell and Cairn would be invited for final
negotiation for Block-5, U.S. companies Triton and UNOCAL and
Malaysian company PTI Oil for Block-7, U.S. company Pangaea Energy
and its Austrian partner OMV for Block-8, and U.S. companies Enron
Oil and Okland International for Blocks-3 and 6.
</P>
<P>
The announcement of the bidding results, which was originally
fixed on December 15 last year, was delayed by seven months, media
reports here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-two foreign companies submitted 37 proposals for 12 out
of the 15 blocks opened in the Second Round Block Bidding in July
last year, and the government invited the bidders for negotiation
in October on a "one company, one block" basis.
</P>
<P>
The companies showed cold shoulders to the remaining three less
perspective blocks, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government had changed the bidding criterion
three times, which some bidders said was deliberately done to
favor certain bidders, hinting at U.S. monopoly in the gas sector
in the South Asian nation.
</P>
<P>
Irish company Tullow Oil and U.S. companies Chevron and Texaco
would be invited to finalize an "unresolved" negotiation for
partnership in Block-9, and a similar decision was taken to
finalize another "unresolved" negotiation for partnership in
Block-11 between Tullow and Malaysian company Petronas and U.S.
company Mobil.
</P>
<P>
In both "unresolved" blocks, Bangladesh's only exploration
unit, BAPEX, had been suggested a 25-percent share, the reports
quoted sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
On Blocks-19 and 20, the government would continue to negotiate
with European company Mearsk Olie before reaching any final
decision, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Blocks-4 and 21 were put out of the bidding as no company was
selected for them, and Block-10, which was earlier decided to be
allocated to Shell and Cairn, was also put out of the bidding. The
authorities had decided to award the block to UNOCAL, with which
the government had initiated a production-sharing contract for a
gas field in the block, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Some energy experts, however, termed the bidding results as
"disastrous." As by the government's experience with Cairn and
Occidental in the past, the production-sharing contracts were not
profitable for the country if they were not modified, they said.
</P>
<P>
The whole county has been divided into 23 blocks for
exploration of gas and oil, of which eight blocks were allotted to
bidders in the first round of bidding, with six awarded to four
U.S. companies and two to a British company.
</P>
<P>
Also on Sunday, Bangladesh signed an agreement with the U.S. on
"Strategic Gas Utilization Study" to identify the uses of the
country's natural gas. The study was expected to be completed by
1999.
</P>
<P>
And U.S. company Mobil Oil and Jamuna Oil Company of Bangladesh
signed an agreement on the same day for setting up an import
terminal for liquefied petroleum gas and two lubricant oil
blending plants in the country's southeastern Chittagong Port.
</P>
<P>
The 25 million U.S.-dollar joint project, which was likely to
be completed by late next year, would initially produce 80,000
tons of liquefied petroleum gas against a current nationwide
demand of 500,000 tons, the reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
