<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia on Kosovo: Consensus First, Talks Later </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav Prime Minister Momir
Bulatovich said Sunday his government will not enter into peace
talks before a consensus is reached on ending terrorism in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In addition to conditioning dialogues with ethnic Albanians,
Bulatovich said there would be no talks with the Kosovo Liberation
Army (KLA) engaging "terrorist activities" in the past five months.
</P>
<P>
Serbian forces have been fighting against the KLA to crush the
latter's efforts seeking independence of the Yugoslav province,
where ethnic Albanians account for 90 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
As extremists among ethnic Albanians are dreaming about a
"Great Serbia," Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic should not
be blamed for the crisis, Bulatovich told the press in Nikssich.
</P>
<P>
If the Republic of Serbia's territorial integrity is observed,
the Kosovo issue should have been solved through dialogues by
granting some extent of autonomy to the province, he was quoted as
saying by the Yugoslav news agency Tanjug. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
