<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Calls for Comprehensive Security in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Foreign Secretary
Domingo Siazon called here Monday for comprehensive and flexible
security in the face of new developments in the Asian-Pacific
region.
</P>
<P>
Siazon, chairman of the Fifth ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF), said
in his opening statement of the one-day ARF that the concept of
regional security the ARF is adopting "should by no means be
limited to political-military security."
</P>
<P>
As the region faces challenges of diverse nature, such as
environmental degradation, natural disasters and economic
slowdown, ASEAN and its dialogue partners and observers must
continually renew their thinking about the nature of security,
Siazon said.
</P>
<P>
"Our paradigm should be flexible enough to allow us to be
responsive to the dynamic nature of the international environment,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
In the ASEAN Ministerial Meeting held here earlier, Thailand
and the Philippines raised the idea of changing ASEAN's
"non-intervention" policy to "flexible engagement" when the
domestic developments in a country have transboundary effects.
</P>
<P>
Most ASEAN countries were strongly opposed to the policy
change.
</P>
<P>
Siazon, however, said the comprehensive security does not mean
that ASEAN and its partners should shelve their traditional
security concerns.
</P>
<P>
"On the contrary, we should revitalize cooperation and dialogue
regarding these traditional concerns," he said.
</P>
<P>
There are many issues in the political-military sphere still
facing the region today, including the current Asian economic
slowdown, disarmament and landmines and nuclear weapons, Siazon
said.
</P>
<P>
The Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) groups
Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
As a multilateral consultative forum aimed at promoting
preventive diplomacy and confidence building among the states in
the region, the ARF consists of the ASEAN member countries, the 10
ASEAN dialogue partners (Australia, Canada, China, the European
Union, India, Japan, New Zealand, South Korea, Russia and the
U.S.) and the two observers (Cambodia and Papua New Guinea).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
