<HEADLINE> Full Text of Chinese FM's Address at ARF (part 1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan made an address at the ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF) which
opened its annual ministerial meeting here Monday morning. The
following is the full text of the address:
Mr. Chairman,
</P>
<P>
It is a great pleasure for me to attend this ARF Ministerial
Meeting as China's new foreign minister. I wish to thank our host,
the government of the Philippines, for its warm hospitality and
thoughtful arrangements for the meeting. I would also like to take
this opportunity to offer, once again, my cordial congratulations
to the Philippines on the centennial of its independence which it
greeted not long ago. I believe that under Chairman Siazon's
outstanding presidency and with the concerted efforts of all ARF
participating countries, this meeting will be a success.
</P>
<P>
The past year has been one of continued significant and
profound changes in the Asia-Pacific region: Major powers have
further readjusted and improved their relations, countries have
strengthened dialogue and cooperation and there have been
gradually deeper-going regional multilateral economic and security
dialogue and cooperation. Peace, development and cooperation
remain the main trend in the regional situation.
</P>
<P>
However, destabilizing factors have apparently increase in the
Asia-Pacific: India and then Pakistan conducted nuclear tests,
plunging South Asia into a sudden wave of tension. As implications
of the financial crisis spread, new problems have cropped up one
after another in the process of regional development. The Cold-War
mentality still has its influence in the region. Such acts as
reinforcing military alliance and interfering in other countries'
internal affairs continue to occur.
</P>
<P>
As it stands, the issues of peace and development are far from
being settled and remain the two major themes confronting us.
</P>
<P>
The practice and experience of the ARF over nearly five years
have shown that in order to secure lasting peace and development
in the Asia-Pacific, it is necessary to nurture a new security
approach and seek new ways of safeguarding Peace:
</P>
<P>
1. To develop state-to-state relations on the basis of the Five

Principles of mutual respect for sovereignty and territorial
integrity,
mutual non-aggression, non-interference in each other's internal
affairs,
equality and mutual benefit, and peaceful coexistence constitutes
the
political foundation and prerequisite of security at both regional
and
international levels. Healthy and stable relations among major
powers and
mutual trust and friendly cooperation among countries of different
types
form an important part of peace and security. In this sense,
improvement
and growth of China-U.S. relations conform to the trend of the
times and
to the fundamental interests of the two peoples and are also
conducive to
regional and world peace and development.
</P>
<P>
2. To increase mutual understanding and trust through dialogue
and
cooperation and undertake to settle state-to-state disputes and
conflicts
through peaceful means are a practical way of ensuring peace and
security.
Security is mutual. History has already proven that the security
concept
and mechanism based on military alliance and achieved through the
build-up of military strength cannot make lasting peace. In this
diversified
region of the Asia-Pacific, it is all the more necessary to work
to
enhance mutual understanding and trust through dialogue and
cooperation.
The act of creating imaginary enemies or fabricating sources of
threat
directed at a third country eventually can only harm others and
more so
oneself.
</P>
<P>
3. Economic growth and common prosperity are the material basis
for
regional and global security. In today's world when the
international
situation moves toward relaxation and economic development faces a
rare
opportunity, to concentrate limited resources on economic and
social
development is an easier way for a country to move into the ranks
of
strong nations of the world, and provides a positive guarantee for

national and regional security as well. If a contrary approach is
adopted,
i.e. insisting on arms expansion, that will not be in keeping with
the
progress of the times. Nor will it help a country to enhance its
national
strength and status. What is more, it may even have a negative
impact on
peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the East Asian financial crisis fully indicates
that
economic security has increasingly become an inseparable part of
national
or regional stability. The East Asian financial crisis broke out
ferociously and has caused such tremendous damage which is no less
than
that of a war. For this reason, the ARF should approach the
subject of
safeguarding economic security in an in-depth manner from the
perspective
of comprehensive security.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
