<HEADLINE> Brazil's Half-Year Coffee Exports Down 28 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Brazil exported 5.4 million
sacks of coffee, each weighing 60 kilograms, in the year's first
six months, down 28 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's Federation of Coffee Exporters said coffee export
earnings in the first six months were 984 million U.S. dollars,
off from the 1.37 billion dollars in the 1997 January-June period.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, earnings from the country's exports of instant
coffee decreased from last year's 153 million dollars to 134
million dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
Experts attributed the drop of coffee exports to the weakening
coffee prices at the international market this year.
</P>
<P>
As the world's number one coffee producer and exporter,
Brazil's annual coffee output is 28 percent of the world's total
and exports are 21 percent of the global coffee trade.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's National Agriculture Confederation said the country's
coffee output this year is estimated to reach 30 million sacks, a
record high in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The trade association expected to see a turn for the better in
the second half of the year and the country's coffee exports in
the six-month period reach the total sum of last year's.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 alone, Brazil sold 14.6 million sacks out of a total of
22 million and pocketed 2.8 billion dollars. The exports and
revenues increased 13 percent and 65 percent respectively from the
previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
