<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese FM Calls for Greater Sino-U.S. Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan Monday called for strengthened cooperation and expanded
consensus between China and the United States, saying the two
countries now have an important opportunity for improving and
promoting their ties.
</P>
<P>
"At present, the relations between our two countries are facing
a major opportunity for further improvement and development," Tang
said while meeting with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
here.
</P>
<P>
He noted that to realize the strategic plan of the two
countries' heads of state concerning the Sino-U.S. ties, "we
should strengthen cooperation, expand consensus, handle
appropriately the differences and problems between the two
countries, remove existing and potential interfering factors and
continue to push forward the Sino-U.S. relationship" on the basis
of the three Sino-U.S. joint communiques and the Sino-U.S. Joint
Statement.
</P>
<P>
Both Tang and Albright are here attending the annual ASEAN
Regional Forum meeting and Post-Ministerial Meeting between member
countries and dialogue partners of the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
Tang noted that it was the first meeting between the Chinese
foreign minister and U.S. secretary of state after President Bill
Clinton's state visit to China and he pledged to work together
with Secretary of State Albright in promoting further improvement
and development of the relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He described as "very successful" President Clinton's visit,
which took place not long ago, saying it marked a new phase in the
Sino-U.S. ties.
</P>
<P>
Tang said that during the visit, the heads of state of the two
countries decided to step up their effort for building a
constructive partnership between China and the United States and
reached major consensus on the expansion of cooperation and
exchange in wide-ranging areas.
</P>
<P>
The visit achieved positive and constructive results and won
widespread welcome from the two peoples and the international
community, he declared.
</P>
<P>
Albright agreed to Foreign Minister Tang's views. She thanked
the Chinese government and people for the work they had done for
President Clinton's visit.
</P>
<P>
The hospitality of the Chinese people and the beautiful scenery
of China left deep impressions on President Clinton and his party,
she said.
</P>
<P>
She pointed out that the U.S.-Chinese relations are moving in a
positive direction.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary of state said the U.S. Congress has passed
legislation to change what used to be called Most Favored Nation
(MFN) status to "normal trade relations" (NTR) and vetoed a bill
calling for an end to China's MFN status.
</P>
<P>
This shows that economic cooperation and trade between the two
countries and their relationship as a whole are witnessing sound
development.
</P>
<P>
Tang and Albright also exchanged views on the latest
developments in the situation in South Asia following the nuclear
tests carried out by India and Pakistan in May.
</P>
<P>
They shared the view that the objectives set out in the joint
communique issued by the foreign ministers of the five permanent
members of the U.N. Security Council -- Britain, China, France,
Russia and the United States -- at their meeting in Geneva earlier
this year and U.N. Security Council Resolution 1172 denouncing the
tests should be maintained.
</P>
<P>
The two sides expressed readiness to work together with the
international community and urge India and Pakistan to implement
the demands raised by the two documents as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to keep in touch and exchange views concerning the
situation in South Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
