<HEADLINE> Security Tightened in Colombo For SAARC Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Police and the armed
forces have tightened security in Colombo, Sri Lanka's capital
city, for the upcoming 10th South Asian association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) here, police sources said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The sources said police and the army personnel, in a joint
operation in connection with the SAARC summit meeting scheduled to
begin on July 29, searched all private and public vehicles
entering Colombo and some vehicles in the city from Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
"we have to search the passengers and their baggage. Sorry for
the inconvenience caused. These measures are for your security.
please bear with us," top police official Jagath Jayawardena said
in an appeal to the public.
</P>
<P>
He requested the public to cooperate with the police and the
armed forces at check points to prevent rebel attacks and traffic
snarls.
</P>
<P>
Over 6,000 police and a vast amount of armed forces have been
deployed in the city Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the month of July is also considered an unlucky one
for Sri Lanka. It was a clash between Sinhales and Tamils in
Colombo in July 1983 that marked an escalation in the country's
Long running civil war, local press reported.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam has been
staging spectacular attacks each year in Colombo to mark the
"Black July" towards the end of the month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
