<HEADLINE> An ASEAN Work Committee to Meet in Myanmar for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Work Committee of the Heads of
Investment Agencies (HIA) of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) will meet here in August to make preliminary
discussions on drafting of an agreement for the grouping's
Investment Area, the official New Light of Myanmar newspaper
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 7th meeting of the ASEAN HIA work committee will be a
follow-up of the 4th ASEAN HIA meeting held last Friday in
Singapore, attended by Myanmar Deputy Prime Minister and Chairman
of the Myanmar Investment Commission Vice-Admiral Maung Maung Khin
among others.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN HIA meeting reportedly discussed the impact of the
regional financial crisis on direct foreign investment of ASEAN,
drafting of agreement on ASEAN Investment Area, promotion of
foreign investment within and outside the region, cooperation
among ASEAN nations, fixing order, investment issues under
discussion at the Organizations for Economic Cooperation and
Development and the World Trade Organization, and preparations for
the ASEAN Summit.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar was admitted into the ASEAN in July last year, before
which some of the ASEAN countries had made investments in Myanmar
since the country opened its door to the outside world in late
1988, adopting the market-oriented economic system.
</P>
<P>
Up to the end of March this year, other five ASEAN fellow
member countries -- Indonesia, the Philippines, Malaysia,
Singapore and Thailand -- injected in Myanmar a total of more than
3.3 billion U.S. dollars in 140 projects, accounting for 45
percent of the 7-billion-dollar total foreign investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
