<HEADLINE> Fallen Officers to be Honored in Capitol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Two Capitol officers cut down
in a burst of gunfire Friday will be honored Tuesday at a special
ceremony at the Capitol where they worked and died.
</P>
<P>
Their remains will lie in honor in the Capitol Rotunda, where
the coffins of presidents and commanding generals have rested.
</P>
<P>
Capitol Police Chief Gary Abrecht announced plans to
memorialize the two "fallen heroes" as the suspect in the
shooting, Russell E. Weston Jr., lay in a hospital bed in serious
condition.
</P>
<P>
Coffins bearing the bodies of officers Jacob J. Chestnut and
John Gibson will be in the Rotunda early Tuesday and remain there
all day.
</P>
<P>
"Those wishing to pay their respects may file past the
remains," Abrecht said. An afternoon service is planned, with
members of Congress, other officers and families of the slain men
in attendance, he said.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton, Vice President Al Gore, House Speaker
Newt Gingrich and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott all are
scheduled to attend the event, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Abrecht said Gibson, 42, will be buried Thursday at a location
to be announced. Chestnut, 58 and an Air Force veteran, will be
interred the following day at Arlington National Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
The two Capitol police officers died of the wounds when the
gunman, a loner with a history of mental illness, burst into the
Capitol Friday afternoon and opened fire with a handgun.
</P>
<P>
The condition of Weston, 41, from Riming, Montana, was upgraded
from critical to serious during the day.
</P>
<P>
Authorities arranged a hearing in absentia for Weston on Monday
in federal court a few blocks from the Capitol. Papers filed in
court in the District of Columbia on Saturday charged him with
killing the two officers. The purpose of Monday's hearing is to
bring the case into federal court.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, tourists roamed the Capitol by the hundreds on
Sunday, some pausing before a pile of flowers that has grown on
the steps outside in tribute to Gibson and Chestnut. 
</P>
</TEXT>
