<HEADLINE> U.S. Scientists Say High Pressure Can Preserve Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 26 (Xinhua) -- After about nine years of
research and two years of testing, U.S. scientists have developed
technology to preserve perishable foods with hydrostatic pressure.
</P>
<P>
The process is able to kill disease-causing microbes such as
E. coli and salmonella, said Sam Huttenbauer Jr., chief executive
officer of High Pressure Research Inc. in Cincinnati on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, "the beauty of this process is that ... it does not
require the preservatives or heat used in more traditional
preservation methods like freezing and canning," Huttenbauer said.
</P>
<P>
Huttenbauer's company is set to commercially produce and market
high-pressure foods in grocery stores later this summer.
</P>
<P>
The technology, as explained by Daniel Farkas, head of the food
science and technology department at the state of Oregon, calls
for placing fresh, packaged food in a water-filled chamber.
</P>
<P>
There in the chamber, he said, the food would be subject to
hydrostatic pressure of 50,000 and 100,000 pounds per square inch,
or 3,518 to 7,036 kilograms per square centimeter.
</P>
<P>
The pressure kills the microbes that spoil food but "does not
alter the food's flavor, appearance, consistency or nutritional
value," said Farkas, a consultant to Huttenbauer's company.
</P>
<P>
The process also reportedly interests the U.S. Army.
</P>
<P>
"We need foods that can be stored up to three years at 80
degrees Fahrenheit (26.7 degrees centigrade)," Patrick Dunne, an
Army chemist in Natick, Massachusetts, told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
"We are especially interested in a yogurt drink and other dairy
products that could be stored unrefrigerated," he said.
</P>
<P>
Initially, high-pressure processed foods will cost 25 to 35
cents more per pound (55 to 77 cents per kilogram) than canned or
frozen foods, but the cost should go down as production goes up,
Huttenbauer said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
