<HEADLINE> ARF Meeting Opens to Discuss Cooperation in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF)
opened its annual meeting here Monday to discuss political and
security cooperation between the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) and its dialogue partners.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting are foreign ministers or representatives
from the nine ASEAN member countries, the two observer nations and
the 10 dialogue partners.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia, whose participation in the ARF was endorsed by the
ASEAN foreign ministers at their two-day ASEAN Ministerial Meeting
ending here on Saturday, has not yet sent a representative this
year.
</P>
<P>
The ARF, which held its first meeting in Bangkok four years
ago, is now participated by the ASEAN's members including Brunei,
Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore,
Thailand and Vietnam; its 10 dialogue partners -- Australia,
Canada, China, the European Union, India, Japan, New Zealand,
Russia, South Korea and the United States -- and its two observers
Cambodia and Papua New Guinea.
</P>
<P>
China obtained its full dialogue partner status in 1996
although it had joined ASEAN member countries as guest during
ASEAN Ministerial Meetings from 1991.
</P>
<P>
Tang Jiaxuan, who became foreign minister earlier this year, is
representing China at the forum for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Initiated by the ASEAN in 1993, the ARF is a consultative forum
aimed at promoting confidence building, developing preventive
diplomacy and working out approaches to conflicts among states in
the Asia-Pacific region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
