<HEADLINE> Heat Wave Even Sets Record During Cool of the Night </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Residents in Texas, of the
southern United States, can't even get relief from the heat wave
during what normally would be the cool of the night.
</P>
<P>
The temperature barely cooled to an overnight low of 28 degrees
centigrade early Sunday, giving the state a record run of 24
consecutive days when it hasn't dropped below 26.6 degrees.
</P>
<P>
The daytime temperature hit 38 degrees centigrade by
midafternoon, the 21st consecutive day of highs above 37.7 degrees
centigrade.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, the heat had been blamed for 141 deaths, including
at least 93 in Texas, news reports said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to contributing to deaths, the heat is blamed for
1.5 billion dollars in agricultural damage and more than 6,765
wildfires in Texas.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman on Sunday issued a federal
disaster declaration for 66 counties in southern and central
Oklahoma. The declaration makes low-interest federal loans
available to farmers who suffered a loss of 30 percent or more on
any single crop.
</P>
<P>
Last week, President Bill Clinton declared all Texas counties
eligible for disaster assistance.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists forecast little if any chance of cooling rain in
the coming week because of a large area of high pressure covering
the South. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
