<HEADLINE> Chinese Win Gymnastics Mixed Pairs at Goodwill Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 26 (Xinhua) -- China's Huang Xu and Ling Jie won the mixed
pairs in the gymnastics competitions at the Goodwill Games in Long Island, New
York on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese pair scored a total of 39.00 points, with Ling winning 19.675
points in uneven bars and balance beam and Huang, 19.325 in parallel bars and
in the pommel horse.
</P>
<P>
Russia's pair Alexei Nemov and Svetlana Khorkina finished second with a
total of 38.725 points. The bronze medal went to Russia's Alexei Bondarenko and
Anna Kovaleva, who gained a collective score of 38.700.
</P>
<P>
It was China's second gold medal in the gymnastics competition following
Huang's victory in the men's individual event of parallel bars on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese pair, who had been fifth after Saturday night's preliminaries,
performed well in both rounds Sunday, finishing second in the first round.
</P>
<P>
"We felt confident going into the second round," Huang told reporters. "We
felt that if we gave our best performances, we would win the gold medal."
</P>
<P>
Parallel bars is Huang's strongest event. Going into the second round with
the event he said he felt very conformable that he could get a high score and
he did it successfully with a high mark of 9.750.
</P>
<P>
Also Ling Jie, whose strongest events are the uneven bars and the balance
beam, beautifully performed in the two events in the last-day competition after
several failures since the start of the Games.
</P>
<P>
She fell from the uneven bars in the preliminaries Saturday night. But her
performance Sunday excited the audience.
</P>
<P>
"I just had to forget about yesterday and think only about today's
competition," Ling said. "I knew if we gave our normal performance, we would
have a good chance at a medal."
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old Chinese girl said she felt "very happy" as it was her first
gold medal in international competition.
</P>
<P>
The Russian pair, Nemov and Khorkina, also had their successful performances
in their strongest events, but the weak ones discounted their scores. Though
Nemov got the men's highest 9.800 points in the high bar, he only gained 9.400
in the floor exercise.
</P>
<P>
The Russian girl scored the women's highest mark, 9.825, in uneven bars, but
her 9.700 points in the balance beam seemed not to her expectation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
