<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BT, AT&AMP;T Forge Global Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 26 (Xinhua) -- British Telecommunications Sunday
unveiled a global joint venture with AT&AMP;T, America's largest
long-distance operator.
</P>
<P>
The newly-allied company, with turnover expected to amount to
10 billion U.S. dollars by 2000, will pool both groups'
international networks, traffic and products to offer a wide range
of telecom and information services to multinational companies.
</P>
<P>
"By positioning ourselves at the forefront of the global
information age, we will maximize opportunities to grow revenues
and enhance profits for shareholders." said Sir Iain Vallance,
BT's chairman, in a statement.
</P>
<P>
BT chief executive Sir Peter Bonfield said services offered by
the new company will include global electronic commerce,
multimedia conferencing and public access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
"We share the conviction that AT&AMP;T and BT can do more together
in the 21st century than either could do on their own.... The
world is too big to do it alone." AT&AMP;T President John Zeglis told
a news conference in London.
</P>
<P>
AT&AMP;T is bringing to the new business the world's largest
telecoms customer base, while BT had become a pioneer in taking
telecoms global and "understands the way the world does business",
Zeglis said.
</P>
<P>
From a base in the United States, the new 50:50 joint venture
will employ 5,000 people by the year 2000, many of them in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The venture, which has yet to be named, will be chaired for the
first two years by BT Chairman Sir Iain Vallance, who will then
hand over to an AT&AMP;T executive.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
